1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 {This is the Slav Defense: Exchange Variation.} 4. Bf4 {This seems to be the best move order for White. As a general rule of thumb for the move orders, if 4...Nc6, Black puts pressure in the center so White plays 5.e3, while if 4...Nf6, Black is gaining control of the e4-square so White plays 5.Nc3.} Nf6 (4... Nc6 5. e3 Bf5 6. Qb3 {When White plays 6.Qb3 immediately against this set-up instead of including 6.Nc3 e6 first, Black doesn't have the move Bb4+ which is very important.} Qd7 7. Nc3 e6 8. Nf3 f6 (8... Nf6 $6 9. Ne5 $16) 9. Bb5 {White has a small advantage and a more pleasant position.}) 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. e3 a6 {This is a typical waiting move that is preventing Nb5 and preparing b7-b5 at some point. It's the main line of this variation. White can reply with 7.Nf3, but it's not the most accurate due to Bg4.} (6... g6 $6 {This is a big positional mistake since the bishop will be misplaced on g7.} 7. h3 {Black may want to play Nh5, so 7.h3 allows the bishop to retreat to the h2-square in case Black plays it. Additionally, it also prevents Bg4 after White develops with Nf3.} Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nf3 a6 10. O-O {White has a big advantage thanks to the difference in strength of the bishops.}) (6... e6 {This is a passive move from Black after which White is positionally better due to the difference in strength of the light-squared bishops.} 7. Bd3 Bd6 8. Bg5 {This is a bit better than 8.Bxd6 in my opinion, although capturing the bishop is also playable.}) (6... Bg4 {After 7.Qb3, it will soon transpose to the line arising from 6...Bf5 7.Qb3.}) (6... Bf5 7. Qb3 (7. Bb5 {This is a simple and very interesting way to play the position without any theory! White plays Bb5 and Nf3, trying to start an attack on the queenside with moves like Ne5, Qa4 or Qb3, 0-0, Rfc1 and so on.}) 7... Na5 {The only good move for Black.} 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qc2 {By an interesting maneuver, White managed to take over the control of the b1-h7 diagonal. From this position, it's not possible and it's impractical to memorize everything that Black can play, so it's simpler to categorize the variations. More analysis can be found in the theoretical file and the commented games.}) 7. Bd3 Bg4 8. Nge2 {White's plan includes typical moves like 0-0, Rc1, a3, Na4, b4, and Nc5. White can possibly consider Bg3 and Nf4 at some point which would activate the knight.} *

