{This is a very nice and easy win by White in the passive e6-Bd6 lines. It's a good demonstration of the typical plans and ideas for White in this variation.} 1. c4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 e6 7. Bd3 Bd6 (7... Be7 {White has a choice between 3 moves in this position: 8.h3, 8.Rc1, and 8.Nf3. The move 8.Rc1 is good but White will need to answer the same question of which move to choose from on the next move. The other two moves are equally good.} 8. Nf3 (8. h3 O-O 9. Nf3 h6 10. Rc1 Nb4 11. Bb1 Bd7 12. O-O Rc8 13. Ne5 $16) 8... Nh5 {After Nh5, almost always White replies with Be5. Even if Black's dark-squared bishop was on f8 instead of e7, it's still very likely that White should prefer Be5 instead of Bg5.} 9. Be5 Nxe5 (9... O-O 10. O-O f6 {Black can play f6 on many occasions, whether earlier or later in the game, so the ideas and type of position matter more than concrete theory.} 11. Bg3 Nxg3 12. hxg3 {Black has created weaknesses with the move f6.} f5 (12... e5 $2 13. dxe5 fxe5 14. Nxd5 $18) (12... Bd7 13. e4 {This is a typical move when Black has the pawns on e6 and f6 in this pawn structure. The weakness of the d4-pawn is compensated by the weak pawn on e6 and slightly exposed king on g8 due to the weaknesses created on the kingside.} dxe4 14. Bxe4 $16) 13. Bb5 {With f5, Black weakened the e5-square and now White will capture the knight on c6, strengthening even further the control of the outpost on e5.}) 10. Nxe5 {This is a logical move that is also playable and leads to an advantage for White.} (10. dxe5 {The best move according to the computer. White is threatening g4 to win the knight.} g6 11. O-O $14) 10... Nf6 11. O-O {11.f4 directly is also good.} O-O {White has a choice of whether to focus on the kingside or the queenside in this position.} 12. Rc1 {This is a useful move in general.} b6 {I wouldn't play Nc6 in this position as the knight is strong and White has better options.} 13. Qe2 {White is focusing on the queenside in this case, and the move 13.Qa4 is also possible and has a similar role in the position.} (13. f4 Bb7 14. Qf3 {Eliminating the possibility of ...Ne4. White wants to continue with g4-g5 next, or even f5 immediately should be considered.}) 13... Bb7 {White can consider playing 14.Ba6 which is a good move, although a route to improving the position can be simply doubling the rooks on the c-file, while it's not so easy for Black to do the same.} 14. Rc2 Rc8 15. Rfc1 $14) 8. Bxd6 {8.Bg5 is a bit better in my opinion.} Qxd6 9. f4 O-O 10. Nf3 b6 11. O-O Bb7 12. Rc1 Rfc8 13. Ne5 Ne7 14. Qf3 {With this move, White prevents any Ne4 ideas from Black.} Qb4 (14... Qd8 {Black has a very good positional idea in mind with this move.} 15. g4 {White continues expanding on the kingside and prevents Black's idea of Nf5-Nd6.} (15. a3 {This is just a move to show Black's idea.} Nf5 {The knight is heading to the d6-square which would give Black firm control over e4.} 16. g4 Nd6 17. f5 {White shouldn't play g5 when the battle for the e4-square has been lost, but instead pushing f5 is the correct approach.} (17. g5 Nfe4 {Black has a good position because of the control of the e4-square and exposed White king.})) 15... a6 16. g5 Nd7 17. Bxh7+ $18) 15. Rb1 Nf5 16. g4 Nd6 17. a3 Qa5 18. f5 exf5 19. Bxf5 Rf8 (19... Nxf5 20. Qxf5 $18) 20. g5 Nfe4 21. Nxe4 Nxe4 22. Bxh7+ Kxh7 23. Qh5+ Kg8 24. Nxf7 Nf6 25. gxf6 (25. Rxf6 gxf6 26. Qg6#) 25... gxf6 26. Qg6# 1-0

