1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 e6 7. Bd3 Be7 8. h3 O-O 9. Nf3 {9.Rc1 is also good.} a6 10. O-O b5 {When Black plays b5, you should always think about playing the move a4, sometimes even if a2-a3 has been played earlier in the position. This is one of the most basic ideas in this variation.} 11. a4 (11. Rc1 {If White doesn't play the move a4 immediately after Black plays b5 for some reason, in that case, the move a4 can always feature in White's plans.} Bb7 12. a4 b4 13. Nb1 $14) 11... b4 12. Nb1 {The knight is heading to the b3-square. It can reach it with Nb1-Nbd2-Nb3 or Na2-Nc1-Nb3.} Bd6 (12... a5 13. Nbd2 {White ignores the supposedly big positional threat of exchanging the light-squared bishops. White is not playing for an attack against the king but on the queenside instead, so allowing that trade is fine.} Ba6 14. Bxa6 {This is better than defending the Bd3 with Nb3. With Bxa6, the rook on a6 will be misplaced and can be attacked at any moment.} Rxa6 15. Nb3 {White has an advantage due to the weak a5-pawn and strong c5-square.} Ne4 16. Nfd2 $16 (16. Qd3 Qa8 17. Rfc1 $16)) 13. Bg5 $2 {So far, White had played a perfect game and had a clear advantage, but now goes wrong with this move.} (13. Bxd6 $1 Qxd6 14. Nbd2 Bb7 (14... Na5 15. Rc1 $1 (15. Nb3 {Is also possible.} Nxb3 16. Qxb3 a5 17. Rfc1 Ba6 18. Ne5 Bxd3 19. Qxd3 Rfc8 20. Qb5 $16) 15... Nd7 16. Qc2 h6 17. Qc7 Qxc7 18. Rxc7 $16 Nb6 19. b3 $18) 15. Nb3 Nd7 (15... a5 16. Nc5 Ra7 17. Rc1 Nd7 18. Nxb7 (18. Nxd7 {Is another good option that White can play.}) 18... Rxb7 19. Qc2 {Wins a pawn due to a double attack.} (19. Bxh7+ {Is also possible. 19...Kxh7 is met by 20. Qc2+, capturing the knight on c6 next.})) 16. a5 $16) 13... h6 14. Bh4 e5 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16. Nxe5 Bxe5 17. Qc1 g5 18. f4 gxh4 19. fxe5 Nd7 20. Qc6 Qg5 21. Qxa8 Nc5 0-1

