1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 e6 5. Nc3 Bd6 6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. e3 Ne7 (7... Nc6 {Now this is a different story where White shouldn't play the move f4 since Black's knight is not on the f6-square.} 8. f4 (8. Bd3 Nf6 (8... Nge7 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O $14) 9. f4 $14) 8... Nge7 {White still probably retains a slight edge, but the point of f4 is to control the e5-square even further, while in this position with the knight on e7, Black can easily play ...f6 at any moment.} 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Bd3 f6 11. O-O {Black has a plan to prepare and play Nf5, or Black can also prepare a break in the center with e6-e5. White has to watch out for different ideas from Black in this position, so playing 8. Bd3 instead of 8.f4 is better.}) 8. Bd3 Nbc6 9. Nf3 $1 {9.f4 doesn't make much sense since Black has developed with Nge7 instead of Nf6, so Black can play f6 at any moment which will fight for control over the e5-square.} f6 (9... O-O 10. O-O a6 11. Rc1 f6 (11... h6 12. a3 f6 (12... b5 13. a4 b4 14. Nb1 a5 15. Nbd2 Ba6 16. Bxa6 Rxa6 17. Nb3 $16) 13. e4 $16) 12. e4 {When Black's pawns are on f6 and e6, White should consider striking in the center with e4! If White can prevent e6-e5 indirectly, with a tactic for example, that would be better and then there would be no need for e3-e4 yet. If White doesn't want to risk or isn't sure, e4 can be played anyway.} dxe4 13. Nxe4 Qd8 14. Bc4 Nd5 15. Re1 Re8 16. Nc3 Nxc3 17. Rxc3 $16) 10. O-O a6 11. e4 $1 {This is a typical reaction in the center if Black plays f6, intending e5.} O-O 12. Re1 $14 dxe4 13. Nxe4 {Recapturing with the knight is a good idea since that knight can go to the c5-square later.} Qb4 (13... Qc7 14. Nc5 {White is targeting the e6-pawn and aims to increase the pressure with Bc4.}) 14. Nc5 $1 e5 15. a3 Qb6 (15... Qxb2 16. Na4 $18) 16. Na4 Qd8 17. dxe5 fxe5 18. Bc4+ Kh8 19. Qxd8 Rxd8 20. Nb6 Bg4 21. Nxa8 Rxa8 22. Nxe5 Nxe5 23. Rxe5 Nc6 24. Re3 Rd8 25. Rae1 Bh5 26. h3 Bg6 27. Bd3 Bf7 28. Kh2 g6 29. Be4 Na5 30. Bf3 Kg8 31. Re7 b5 32. Ra7 Nc4 33. Ree7 Nd6 34. Rxa6 Nf5 35. Rea7 Kg7 36. Rc7 Rd2 37. Rb6 Rxb2 38. Bd5 Nh6 39. Bxf7 Nxf7 40. f3 Kg8 41. Rb8+ Kg7 42. Rbb7 1-0

