1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 a6 7. Bd3 g6 $2 8. h3 Bf5 9. Nf3 $5 (9. Bxf5 $5 {White could have captured on f5 immediately, where probably Black will develop the dark-squared bishop on the other side with e6, although White is still better in that position too.} gxf5 10. Nge2 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. Nc1 $1 $16 {The knight is heading to the d3-square from where it controls and can jump on both the e5 and c5 squares.}) 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Bg7 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfc1 {All of White's pieces are aimed against the queenside.} e6 (12... b5 13. Nxb5 $18) 13. Na4 $14 {Black has already played the move a6, so now b6 isn't possible.} Ne4 14. Nc5 Nxc5 15. Rxc5 Qd7 16. Rac1 Rfc8 {Black's position may appear solid, but the knight from c6 can't retreat due to Rc7, entering the 7th rank.} 17. a3 Bf8 18. R5c2 f6 (18... Na7 19. Rc7 $16) (18... Be7 19. Ne5 {This move needs to be calculated since it may lead to an equal position if White isn't precise.} (19. b4 {This move is also possible.}) 19... Nxe5 20. Bxe5 Rxc2 21. Qxc2 {White has a permanent advantage due to the control of the only open file in the position.} Bd6 22. Bxd6 Qxd6 23. Qc7 Qxc7 24. Rxc7 {White has very good winning chances in this endgame.}) 19. Nd2 {Black created some weaknesses, but in order to make progress, the knight from f3 wasn't doing anything so it needs to be rerouted.} Bd6 $2 20. Bxd6 Qxd6 21. Nb3 Rc7 22. Na5 Rac8 23. Nxb7 $3 {This is a very typical idea in these types of positions! White gets two connected passed pawns and the plan is very simple - to push them, while Black's pieces are tied down and they have to anticipate the a and b-pawns rolling down the board.} Rxb7 24. Qxa6 Rbc7 25. b4 Qd7 26. Qb6 $1 Qe8 (26... Rb8 27. Qxb8+ Nxb8 28. Rxc7 Qd6 29. Rb7 Nc6 (29... Nd7 30. Rc8+ (30. a4 Nf8 31. a5 $18) 30... Kf7 (30... Nf8 31. Rbb8 $18) 31. Rcc7 $18) 30. Rb6 $18) 27. b5 Nxd4 28. Rxc7 Ne2+ 29. Kh1 Nxc1 30. Rxc8 Qxc8 31. Qc6 Qd8 32. b6 Kf7 33. Qc7+ Ke8 34. Qa7 d4 35. b7 1-0

