1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Nc3 Nf6 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Qb3 Na5 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qc2 Rc8 10. Nf3 g6 {Once again, this is a strategically risky move.} 11. Bd3 Bg7 12. h3 (12. O-O {Is also good.}) 12... b5 13. a3 Nc4 14. O-O O-O 15. Rfc1 $1 a6 16. Qe2 (16. Ne5 $5 Nh5 17. Nxd7 Qxd7 18. Bh2 $14) 16... Bf5 17. Ne5 (17. Bxf5 gxf5 18. Ne1 $16 {The knight is heading to the d3-square from where it will be well-placed.}) 17... Nd7 18. Bxf5 $1 gxf5 19. Nd3 $1 $18 {The knight stands perfectly on d3. It's protecting the queenside, jumping on the c5-square can be an option in the future, and preparing for a Nf4-Nh5 maneuver as well!} e6 20. a4 Qb6 21. axb5 axb5 22. b3 Nd6 23. Qa2 Ne4 24. Ne2 Nef6 25. Rc2 Qb7 26. Rac1 Rxc2 27. Qxc2 Ra8 28. Bd6 Ne4 29. Bb4 Bf8 30. Bxf8 Kxf8 31. f3 Nd6 32. Nc5 Qa7 33. Nf4 Nf6 34. Qf2 Qa2 35. Qe1 Qa5 36. Qh4 Nde8 37. Qf2 Qa2 38. Qe1 Nd6 39. Kh2 Qa5 40. Qf2 Ke7 41. Ncd3 Qa2 42. Qh4 Nde8 43. Nh5 Qxb3 44. Nxf6 Qxd3 45. Nxd5+ Kf8 46. Qh6+ Ng7 47. Nf6 Qd2 48. Nxh7+ Ke8 49. Rc7 {This is one of the best games I have ever seen in the Slav Defense: Exchange Variation.} 1-0

