1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 a6 {White shouldn't be afraid of moves like 4...a6 since they are not threatening anything. There's no theory here and White should simply develop the pieces and play chess.} 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. e3 e6 7. Bd3 b5 8. Nf3 Bb7 9. O-O Bd6 10. Ne5 Nc6 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. Bg3 O-O 13. Bb1 {In the game, I focused more on the queenside, but focusing on the kingside is also possible with moves like f4, Bh4, and Qd3 at some point.} Ne7 14. Nd3 Nf5 15. Bxd6 Nxd6 16. Ne2 Qb6 17. Nc5 {The knight is strong on c5 and gives White an advantage.} Rc7 18. Nf4 a5 19. Nh5 Nxh5 20. Qxh5 g6 $2 (20... h6 $14) 21. Qg5 $16 Ne4 22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. h4 Rfc8 24. h5 Rf8 25. Qf6 gxh5 26. f3 $1 Qd6 27. Nxb7 Rxb7 28. Rc5 h6 29. Rxh5 1-0

