1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 {This is the Slav Defense: Exchange Variation.} cxd5 {White can choose whether to play this variation with a quick Nf3 in the upcoming several moves or White can delay Nf3 which is more ambitious and can possibly take advantage of that.} 4. Bf4 {This seems to be the best move order for White. With 4.Nf3, White will lose some flexibility in this set-up, while 4.Nc3 is possible but it allows the extra option 4...e5 for Black which is an extra line to study, so 4.Bf4 develops the bishop and prevents that move. As a general rule of thumb for the move orders, if 4...Nc6, Black puts pressure in the center so White plays 5.e3, while if 4...Nf6, Black is gaining control of the e4-square so White plays 5.Nc3.} Nf6 (4... Qb6 5. Nc3 Qxb2 $2 6. Nxd5 $18) (4... Nc6 $1 5. e3 Bf5 $1 {This is a very interesting system for Black. The idea is that Black is trying to play without the move Nf6 and will probably play Nge7 at some point. Surprisingly, the most natural move 6.Nc3 is not the best. The only move to pose Black problems is 6.Qb3!} 6. Qb3 $1 {When White plays Qb3 immediately against this set-up, Black doesn't have the move Bb4+ which is very important.} (6. Nc3 $6 e6 7. Qb3 Bb4 $1 $132 8. Bb5 $6 {Threatening to capture the bishop on b4.} Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 Rc8 $1 10. Nf3 a6 $1 $15) 6... Qd7 (6... Qb6 7. Qxb6 axb6 {This endgame is always pleasant for White.} 8. Nc3 e6 9. Bb5 {White doesn't want to capture the knight on c6 but is simply developing, gaining further control on the queenside, and pinning the knight on c6.} (9. f3 $14 {Intending to expand on the kingside is also possible.}) 9... Nf6 10. f3 Bb4 11. Nge2 $16) (6... e5 $5 {This is objectively a bad move, but White needs to know how to reply!} 7. dxe5 Bxb1 (7... g5 $5 8. Bg3 h5 9. h4 d4 10. Bc4 Qa5+ 11. Kf1 O-O-O 12. Ne2 $16) 8. Rxb1 Bb4+ 9. Kd1 $18 {White can't castle anymore but the position is winning for White.} d4 (9... g5 10. Bg3 Nge7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Ke2 Qd7 13. Nf3 $18) 10. e4 $1 {This is a strong move, although it's not the strongest according to the computer, it's a very human way to play. White doesn't allow Black the opportunity to open up the position while White's king is in the center.} Nge7 11. Nf3 O-O (11... Ng6 12. Bg3 O-O 13. a3 Ba5 14. Qxb7 Rc8 15. Bd3 Re8 16. Rc1 $18) 12. Bd3 a5 13. a3 a4 14. Qc4 Ba5 15. e6 $1 (15. Ke2 $2 Ng6 16. Bg3 Bc7 $132) 15... fxe6 16. Qxe6+ Kh8 17. Bg3 Bc7 18. e5 Ra5 19. Re1 Nd5 20. Qh3 h6 21. Qg4 $18) 7. Nc3 {After including the moves Qb3 and Qd7, only now White plays Nc3.} e6 (7... Nf6 $2 8. Nf3 e6 9. Ne5 Qc8 (9... Nxe5 $4 10. dxe5 Ne4 11. Bb5 $18) 10. Rc1 $16) 8. Nf3 f6 (8... Nf6 $6 9. Ne5 $16) 9. Bb5 $1 {White has a small advantage and a more pleasant position.} Rc8 (9... a6 $6 10. Bxc6 Qxc6 11. O-O Ne7 12. Rfc1 Rc8 (12... Qd7 $6 13. Na4 $18) 13. Nh4 $1 Bg4 14. h3 $1 Bh5 15. e4 $3 $18) (9... Nge7 10. Na4 $5 (10. O-O $14) 10... Ng6 11. O-O $1 Nxf4 12. exf4 Bd6 13. Rfc1 $1 O-O (13... Bxf4 14. Nc5 $16 {[%cal Gc5b7]}) 14. Nc5 $14) 10. O-O a6 11. Bxc6 Rxc6 12. Rfc1 Ne7 13. Na4 $14) 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. e3 a6 $1 {This is a typical waiting move that is preventing Nb5 and preparing b7-b5 at some point. It's the main line of this variation. White can reply with 7.Nf3, but it's not the most accurate due to Bg4. My recommendation is 7.Bd3, but White also has two other playable moves.} (6... Bg4 {After 7.Qb3, it will soon transpose to the line arising from 6...Bf5 7.Qb3. In that variation from 6...Bf5, White had the extra possibility 7.Bb5 which is not possible here because the queen is attacked.} 7. Qb3 $5 (7. f3 {7.Qb3 is the best move, but this is an option to combine with 6...Bf5 7.Bb5, although it's not as good as the main line but it is playable.} Bf5 8. g4 Bg6 9. h4 h6 10. Rc1 e6 11. Nh3 Be7 12. Bg3 $14) 7... Na5 (7... Qb6 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. h3 Bd7 10. Nf3 $14 (10. Rc1 {Is also possible.} e6 11. a3 $14)) 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qc2 {Transposes to the line 6.e3 Bf5 7.Qb3 Na5.}) (6... Qb6 $6 {This is a rare move on which White has a choice of different moves to choose from.} 7. Bd3 $1 {This is the best move. White sacrifices the pawn on b2 and if Black doesn't capture it soon, later on, the move Na4 and White's queenside expansion will come with tempo.} (7. Qd2 {Defending the b2-pawn is also a simple continuation. White intends to continue with moves like Bd3 and f3.}) (7. Bb5 $5 {The second-best move in the position. White wants to follow up with Nge2 or Nf3 next.} Bd7 (7... a6 8. Bxc6+ Qxc6 9. Rc1 Qb6 10. Nf3 $16) 8. a3 a6 9. Bd3 $14) 7... Qxb2 8. Nge2 $16 {White has the initiative and already Nb5-Nc7 in a threat.}) (6... e6 $6 {This is a passive move from Black after which White is positionally better due to the difference in strength of the light-squared bishops.} 7. Bd3 $1 Bd6 (7... Be7 $5 8. h3 $1 (8. Nf3 $5 $14 Nh5 9. Be5 O-O 10. O-O Nxe5 11. dxe5 $16 (11. Nxe5 Nf6 12. f4 $14)) 8... O-O 9. Nf3 a6 10. O-O b5 11. a4 b4 12. Nb1 a5 13. Nbd2 $16) (7... a6 {Now White has a choice of many different moves.} 8. Rc1 $1 {This is a useful move in general. If Black continues with 8...Bd6, after 9.Bxd6 it will be the same as the variation 7...Bd6 but with the moves a6 and Rc1 included, where Rc1 is much more useful than a6. Additionally, White doesn't need to think about Nb4 anymore since Bb1 is a good reply which won't block the rook from a1 as the rook has already been developed on c1.}) 8. Bg5 $1 {This is a bit better than 8.Bxd6 in my opinion.} (8. Bxd6 $5 {This is also a good option that White can play.} Qxd6 9. f4 $1 {This is one difference when the knight hasn't committed to the f3-square yet, f4! is possible immediately! White wants to play a quick Nf3-Ne5 next.} O-O 10. Rc1 a6 11. Nf3 b5 12. Ne5 Bb7 13. O-O b4 14. Na4 $16) 8... h6 9. Bh4 {White doesn't want to capture the knight on f6 until Black plays Be7.} O-O 10. f4 Be7 {Black has unpinned the knight and wants to play the maneuver Ne8-Nd6 which would improve Black's position, so now White should capture on f6.} 11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. Nf3 $14) (6... Bf5 {This move is similar to 6...Bg4. When Black's light-squared bishop has developed actively, there is no attack against Black's king and Black's queenside becomes vulnerable.} 7. Qb3 $1 {The main line.} (7. Bb5 $5 {This is a simple and very interesting way to play the position without any theory! White plays Bb5 and Nf3, trying to start an attack on the queenside with moves like Ne5, Qa4 or Qb3, 0-0, Rfc1, and so on. There are sample lines below. Black may reach equality or a slightly worse position if Black knows everything, but it's unlikely and the advantage is that it's very easy to play with White.} e6 (7... Rc8 8. Nf3 a6 (8... e6 9. Ne5 Be7 {This is a natural developing move which in fact loses an exchange. Black needs to play accurately on the 7.Bb5 move.} 10. Nxc6 bxc6 11. Ba6 $18) 9. Bxc6+ {This is a very typical idea, White captures on c6, plays Ne5 with tempo, and focuses entirely on the queenside.} Rxc6 10. Ne5 Rc8 11. Qb3 b5 12. O-O e6 13. Rfc1 {This rook goes to the c-file since the other one may support a4 later.} (13. a4 $2 {White needs to be careful of this tactic.} b4 14. Na2 Bc2 $19 {[%csl Rb3]}) 13... Be7 14. Nxb5 $3 {This move is winning by force.} (14. Ne2 {If for some reason White didn't have a winning tactic with 14.Nxb5, this move shows that White still has a big advantage in the position.} Rxc1+ 15. Rxc1 O-O 16. Nc6 Qd7 17. Nxe7+ Qxe7 18. Rc7 $18 {18.Bg5 is also an idea where White will avoid an opposite-colored bishop endgame, and the knight will be stronger than the bishop on f5 isn't contributing to the game.}) 14... axb5 15. Qxb5+ Kf8 16. Qb7 Rb8 17. Nd7+ Nxd7 18. Bxb8 $18) (7... Qb6 8. Nf3 a6 (8... e6 9. Ne5 $16) 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 (9... Qxc6 10. Ne5 $18) 10. O-O {This is a very typical idea, abandoning the b2-pawn for one move. If 10.Na4 instead, Black can give a check on b4 which is annoying to deal with.} Qxb2 11. Na4 Qc2 12. Qxc2 Bxc2 13. Nb6 Ra7 14. Rfc1 {Black is about to pay the price for being undeveloped.} Be4 15. Rxc6 $18) (7... Bd7 8. Nf3 a6 (8... e6 {When White sees this move with the bishop on d7, White needs to be prepared to go back with the bishop from b5 instead of exchanging it, although it's better to wait for the move a6 in order to gain a tempo.} 9. Rc1 Be7 10. h3 O-O 11. O-O a6 12. Bd3 $3 $14 {With the pawn on e6, the bishop on d7 is stuck inside Black's pawn chain, so that's a big difference that White uses by retreating the bishop! Additionally, White may have good attacking chances on the kingside.} Rc8 {White should consider moves like Ne5 or Bb1, possibly even creating a battery along the b1-h7 diagonal.} (12... b5 13. a4 b4 14. Nb1 Qa5 {Black is trying to prevent the Nbd2-Nb3 maneuver, saying that the a4-pawn will be hanging, but White has a good continuation.} 15. Nbd2 Rfc8 (15... Na7 16. Ra1 (16. Bc7 {White should always calculate the move Bc7 in case it wins concretely, but in this position it doesn't bring much, so 16.Ra1 is better.}) 16... Rfc8 17. Nb3 Qb6 18. Ne5 (18. Qe2 {Immediately is also possible.}) 18... Be8 19. Qe2 a5 {White is better and can consider harassing the rook on c8 with:} 20. Ba6 $16) 16. Nb3 Qxa4 $2 (16... Qb6 17. Qe2 $16) 17. Ra1 $18 {[%csl Ra4]}) 13. Bb1 h6 14. Ne5 {In case Black plays the move h6, it creates a hook that White can use by bringing the queen to the kingside with Qf3, or g4 directly is also an idea.}) 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. Ne5 Rc8 (10... e6 {White has several good moves in the position, such as 11.Qb3, 11.0-0, and 11. Nxc6 is also good.} 11. Qb3 Bd6 {Black may want to capture the knight on e5, where the position will be around equal, perhaps slightly preferable for White, so now it's a good moment to capture on c6.} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. O-O O-O 15. Na4 {Preventing c5 and preparing to put pressure on the weak c6-pawn down the c-file.} Rab8 (15... Nd7 16. Rac1 Rfc8 17. Qc3 $14) 16. Qc2 $14 {White has a risk-free game where White will put a lot of pressure on the c6-pawn and perhaps will even triple on the c-file.}) 11. O-O {11.Qb3 is also possible.} e6 12. Qb3 $14 {White already has ideas of capturing the bishop on c6, while it's difficult to find good moves for Black in this position.} b5 13. Rfc1 $16) 8. Nf3 Nd7 (8... a6 9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qa4 $16) (8... Rc8 9. Ne5 Bd6 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. O-O O-O 12. Rc1 $14 {[%csl Gc5][%cal Gc3a4]} c5 $6 13. Nb5 $16) (8... Bg4 {Black would like to play this move but there simply isn't enough time for Black to move twice with the same piece in the opening.} 9. Qa4 Bxf3 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. Qxc6+ Nd7 12. gxf3 $18) (8... Bd6 9. Qa4 (9. Bxc6+ bxc6 10. Qa4 Qc7 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Ne5 ({Another possibility is:} 12. O-O O-O 13. Qa5 Rfb8 14. Na4 Nd7 15. Rfc1 $14 {With a small but stable advantage.}) 12... Rc8 13. Qxa7 O-O 14. Qc5 $16) 9... Qd7 10. Ne5 Bxe5 11. Bxe5 O-O 12. Bxc6 Qxc6 13. Qxc6 bxc6 14. f3 (14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Na4 Rab8 16. b3 e5 17. Kd2 Rfe8 18. f3 $16 exd4 19. exd4 Rb4 20. Kc3 a5 21. Rhe1 $18) 14... Nd7 15. Bd6 Rfd8 $16) 9. O-O Rc8 10. Qb3 $14) 7... Na5 {The only good move for Black.} (7... Qd7 $2 {Runs into a quick Nf3-Ne5 idea.} 8. Nf3 e6 9. Ne5 Qc8 (9... Nxe5 $2 10. dxe5 $18 {[%cal Ge5f6,Gf1b5,Gb5e8]}) 10. Rc1 Be7 11. Bb5 $16) (7... Qb6 $6 8. Qxb6 axb6 9. Bb5 {White has a very pleasant position.} e6 10. Nge2 Be7 11. f3 $14) (7... Qc8 $6 8. Rc1 {White plans to develop the light-squared bishop to b5 or e2.} (8. Nb5 $1 e5 9. dxe5 Bb4+ 10. Qxb4 Nxb4 11. Nd6+ Kf8 12. Nxc8 Nc2+ 13. Ke2 Rxc8 (13... Nxa1 14. Nd6 $18) 14. Rc1 Ne4 15. f3 Nc5 16. Kd2 Nb4 17. Rc3 $16) 8... e6 9. Nf3 $16) 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qc2 $1 {By an interesting maneuver, White managed to take over the control of the b1-h7 diagonal. From this position, it's not possible and it's impractical to memorize everything that Black can play, so it's simpler to categorize the variations. There are two types of variations: lines where Nc4 is played sooner or later, or lines where Nc6 is played sooner or later. Black can start with various move orders.} Rc8 $5 {Now both 10.Bd3 and 10.Nf3 are good for White.} (9... e6 $5 10. Bd3 Nc6 (10... Nh5 11. Be5 Nc6 12. Qe2 $1 {It's not an issue if Black captures the dark-squared bishop on e5, but it is a problem if Black goes for the light-squared bishop on d3 with Nb4, so that's why the queen stepped away from the c2-square.} (12. a3 $14) 12... Nf6 13. Bg3 Be7 14. Nf3 O-O 15. h3 $14) 11. a3 (11. Qd1 $5 $14) 11... Nh5 12. Bg3 (12. Be5 $5) 12... Be7 (12... Nxg3 13. hxg3 g6 14. f4 Bg7 15. g4 $1 $14) 13. Qe2 Nxg3 14. hxg3 g6 15. f4 $14) 10. Bd3 (10. Nf3 $5 {This will most likely transpose to 10.Bd3.} Nc4 $2 {This move is generally a mistake. If Black wants to play it, Black should include the moves b7-b5 (threatening b4) and a2-a3.} 11. Bxc4 {Now both recaptures 11...Rxc4 and 11...dxc4 lead to problems for Black.} Rxc4 (11... dxc4 12. O-O e6 13. e4 $16 {White takes over the center and has a big advantage. At some point, White should consider playing the move d5.}) 12. Ne5 Rc8 13. Qb3 {13.0-0 is also possible, although 13.Qb3 puts pressure on Black's queenside immediately.} Bc6 14. O-O e6 15. Rfc1 $16 {15.h3 is also a good move. White can capture the bishop on c6 at some point where Black will be forced to recapture with the pawn since Rxc6 will be met with Qxb7, so Black will have a weak pawn on c6 and a weak c5-square.}) 10... e6 (10... Nc6 11. a3 e6 12. Nf3 Be7 (12... Nh5 13. Be5 $1 (13. Bg5 Be7 (13... f6 14. Bxh7 fxg5 15. Qg6+ $18) 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Ne5 Nf6 16. h3 $14) 13... f6 14. Bg3 $14) 13. h3 $1 {This is simpler and better than 13.0-0.} (13. O-O $5 Nh5 14. Be5 f6 15. Bg3 f5 16. Be5 $1 O-O 17. Rfc1 $1 {There are many games starting from this position where White is slightly better with many logical moves.} (17. b4 $5 {Is also interesting.} g5 18. Rfc1 g4 19. b5 $1 gxf3 20. bxc6 Bxc6 21. Qd1 $3 $16) 17... g5 (17... Nf6 18. Qb3 (18. Qd1 $14) 18... Na5 19. Qa2 Ne4 20. Ne2 $14) 18. b4 g4 19. b5 Na5 (19... gxf3 20. bxc6 Bxc6 21. Qd1 Bf6 22. Bxf6 Nxf6 23. Qxf3 Kh8 24. Ne2 Ne4 25. Nf4 $16) (19... Nb8 20. Bxb8 gxf3 21. Be5 fxg2 22. Qd1 Be8 23. Ne2 $14) (19... Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Bd6 21. Qd1 $14 (21. Qd2 $14)) 20. Nd2 $16) 13... O-O 14. O-O a6 15. Qe2 $14 (15. Rac1 $14) 15... Na5 16. Ne5 b5 17. Rac1 Nc4 18. Rfd1 Be8 19. e4 dxe4 20. Nxe4 Nd5 21. Bg3 Nxe5 22. dxe5 $16) 11. Nf3 b5 {This is a possible idea from Black, threatening b4.} (11... Bb4 12. O-O O-O 13. Rfc1 h6 14. h3 Bxc3 15. bxc3 b5 16. Ne5 (16. Qe2 $14) 16... Nc4 17. Bxc4 bxc4 18. Rcb1 $14) 12. a3 Be7 13. O-O O-O 14. Ne5 (14. Rfc1 $5 Nc4 15. Ne5 (15. Qe2 $14) 15... a6 16. Qe2 $14) 14... Nc4 15. Qe2 $14 {Sooner or later White needs to move the queen away from the firing range of Black's rook on the c-file. Now the plan is to dislodge the knight from c4 with the move a4, and if needed, White will capture the bishop on d7. Here are some sample lines of how to fight for the initiative with White.} Be8 (15... a5 $2 16. a4 b4 17. Nb5 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 Qb6 19. Rfc1 $16) (15... Nxa3 $2 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Nxb5 Nxb5 18. Bxb5 Qd8 19. Rxa7 $16) (15... a6 $6 16. a4 $1 b4 17. Nb1 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 $1 {White should recapture with the bishop since 18.dxe5 would make the dark-squared bishop on f4 very passive.} a5 19. Nd2 Qb6 (19... Qe8 20. Nb3 Bxa4 21. Nxa5 Ra8 22. Nb7 Nd7 23. Bg3 $14) 20. Nb3 h6 21. Bb5 $16 (21. Ba6 {This move also deserves some attention and during a game should be calculated whether it's more precise than Bb5 or not.} Ra8 22. Bb5 Bxb5 23. Qxb5 Qxb5 24. axb5 a4 25. Nc5 $18 {[%csl Gb6,Gb7,Gb8][%cal Gb5b6] It's very difficult for Black to stop the b5-pawn from promoting.})) (15... h6 $2 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. b3 $1 Nxa3 (17... Nxe3 18. Bxb5 (18. Qxe3 Rxc3 19. Bh7+ $18)) 18. Nxb5 Nxb5 19. Bxb5 Qd8 20. Ra6 $16 {This move is more accurate according to the engine, preventing Bd6.} (20. Rxa7 $14 {Capturing the pawn is logical and also playable.})) 16. Rfc1 $1 Qb6 17. a4 $14 (17. Rc2 $14) 17... b4 18. Nd1 $1 Nd6 19. Rxc8 Nxc8 20. Qc2 Nd6 21. a5 Qb7 22. Rc1 $18) (6... g6 $6 {This is a big positional mistake since the bishop will be misplaced on g7.} 7. h3 $1 {Black may want to play Nh5, so 7.h3 allows the bishop to retreat to the h2-square in case Black plays it. Additionally, it also prevents Bg4 after White develops with Nf3.} Bg7 8. Bd3 {The best move order for White.} O-O 9. Nf3 a6 (9... Bf5 {Even in a scenario where Black captures on d3 and exchanges the light-squared bishops, White will still be better as the bishop on f4 is much more active than its counterpart.} 10. Bxf5 gxf5 11. g4 $3 $16 {White uses the pawn on f5 as a hook to open up the kingside. White has a very strong attack.}) 10. O-O {White has a big advantage thanks to the difference in strength of the bishops.} b5 {After b5, White aims to play a4 directly or Rc1 first and then a4.} 11. Rc1 Bb7 12. a4 $1 $16 {The computer suggests a move like 12.Ne5, but our play is based on plans and ideas.} b4 13. Nb1 a5 14. Nbd2 $16) 7. Bd3 $1 {White doesn't need to memorize much theory after this move, the plans and ideas are more important!} (7. Nf3 Bg4 $1 8. Be2 Bxf3 $1 9. Bxf3 e6 $11) (7. Rc1 $5 {The usual move which improves White's position is also playable.}) (7. Be2 $5 {The idea is to wait for Black to develop the bishop with Bf5, and only then to develop with Nf3, discouraging the move Bg4 since it would lose a tempo.}) 7... Bg4 {The only good move for Black.} (7... g6 $6 8. h3 $1 $14 {After g6, White has enough time to play h3 and save the dark-squared bishop in case Black plays Nh5.}) (7... e6 $6 8. Rc1 $1 $14) 8. Nge2 {White's plan includes moves like 0-0, Rc1, a3, Na4, b4, and Nc5. White can possibly consider Bg3 and Nf4 at some point which would activate the knight.} e6 (8... Nh5 $2 9. f3 Nxf4 (9... Bc8 10. Bg5 $1 $16) 10. Nxf4 $14) 9. Rc1 (9. Qb3 $6 {This move isn't working very well for White in this position.} Na5 10. Qa4+ b5 11. Bxb5+ $2 axb5 12. Nxb5 Nc6 (12... Nd7 $2 13. Nc7+ Ke7 14. Nxa8 Qxa8 15. f3 Bf5 16. b4 $18) 13. Nc7+ Kd7 14. Nxa8 $17) 9... Be7 (9... Bxe2 $5 10. Qxe2 Bd6 11. Bg5 $5 {Surprisingly, the dark-squared bishops will be exchanged anyway, but White gains some time with this move.} (11. Bxd6 $5 Qxd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Na4 Nd7 (13... Rac8 14. Nc5 Rc7 15. Rc3 e5 16. Rfc1 exd4 $6 17. Nxb7 Rxb7 18. Rxc6 $16 Qe5 19. Bxa6 Rbb8 20. b3 $16) 14. Rc3 g6 {Black played g6 because the pawn on h7 may be hanging in some lines, for example Black may need to be careful of Qc2 at some point.} 15. Rfc1 Rac8 16. a3 Rfe8 (16... Ne7 17. b4 Rxc3 18. Rxc3 Rc8 19. Nc5 b6 $2 (19... Rc7 20. Qc2 $14) (19... Nxc5 20. bxc5 Qd7 21. Rb3 $14) 20. Bxa6 Rc7 21. Nb7 Rxc3 22. Nxd6 $18) 17. Nc5 $1 {White has occupied the c-file and this is a type of position with a light-squared bishop against the knight, however, sometimes it can occur that White has either a dark-squared bishop or a knight versus Black's knight. In all three cases, White has a slight advantage. In addition, the pawn on a6 may be hanging tactically in some lines.} (17. h3 $14) (17. Qd2 Ne7 18. b4 Rxc3 19. Rxc3 $14) 17... Nxc5 18. Rxc5 Rc7 19. Bxa6 $5 {White will have very strong compensation for the piece with the two connected passed pawns.} (19. b4 {This is another good option for White.}) 19... bxa6 20. Qxa6 Rec8 21. b4 Qd7 22. Qa4 {This is a very interesting idea from White. The queen is heading to the c2-square from where the knight will be pinned, and White will threaten b5. Additionally, after b5, Black may reply with Nxd4, and because White has the time, improving with Qc3 first might be an idea.} Kf8 23. Qc2 Ke7 24. Qc3 Kd8 25. b5 Ne7 26. Qb4 $18) 11... h6 (11... O-O 12. O-O Be7 13. Na4 h6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nc5 Qe7 16. a3 e5 17. dxe5 Bxe5 18. Rfd1 d4 19. e4 $14) 12. Bh4 Be7 (12... O-O 13. O-O Qb6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Nxd5 $18) 13. O-O O-O 14. a3 (14. Na4 $5 Nd7 15. Bg3 (15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. a3 e5 17. dxe5 (17. Bf5 $5 Nf6 18. dxe5 Qxe5 19. Bd3 $14) 17... Ndxe5 18. Bb1 Rad8 (18... d4 $2 19. exd4 Nxd4 20. Qe4 $18) 19. Rfd1 d4 20. Nc5 dxe3 21. Qxe3 $14) 15... Qa5 (15... Nb6 16. Nc5 $16) 16. Qd1 (16. Nc3 $5 Rac8 17. a3 Qd8 18. Bb1 $5 (18. h3 $14) 18... Nb6 19. Qd3 g6 20. Ne2 $14) 16... Rac8 17. a3 $14) (14. Bxf6 $5 Bxf6 15. Na4 e5 (15... Rc8 16. a3 $1 (16. Nc5 Qe7 (16... Qc7 17. a3 (17. Nxb7 $2 Nxd4 $19) 17... Be7 18. b4 Bxc5 19. Rxc5 $14) 17. Rfd1 (17. Nxb7 $6 Nxd4 $15) 17... e5 18. Bf5 Rc7 19. dxe5 Qxe5 20. Bg4 Qxb2 $6 21. Rc2 Qa3 22. Nd7 $16) 16... Be7 (16... e5 17. dxe5 Nxe5 18. Bb1 $14) 17. b4 g6 18. Nc5 Bxc5 19. Rxc5 Qd7 20. Qg4 (20. Rfc1 {This is also an interesting possibility for White.} e5 (20... Ne7 21. Qb2 Rxc5 22. bxc5 (22. dxc5 $5 Nc6 23. a4 $14 e5 $2 24. b5 $18) 22... Rc8 23. Rb1 Rc7 24. g3 $14) 21. dxe5 Nxe5 22. h3 $14) 20... Kg7 21. Rfc1 $14) (15... Be7 16. a3 $1 Rc8 17. b4 $14 (17. Rc2 $5 Na5 18. Rxc8 Qxc8 19. b4 $1 Nc6 20. Qc2 $14) (17. Nc5 $5 Bxc5 18. Rxc5 Rc7 19. Rfc1 Qd6 20. Bxa6 bxa6 21. Qxa6 Rfc8 22. b4 $16) 17... g6 18. Nc5 Bxc5 19. Rxc5 $14) (15... Qa5 $6 16. Nc5 $14 Qxa2 $2 17. Ra1 $18) 16. dxe5 Bxe5 17. g3 $1 (17. Rfd1 $6 Bxh2+ 18. Kxh2 Qh4+ $15) 17... d4 18. Rfd1 $14 (18. e4 $14)) (14. f4 $5 $14) 14... Nd7 (14... Rc8 15. Na4 Nd7 16. Bg3 Bh4 17. Bxh4 Qxh4 18. Nc5 Nxc5 19. Rxc5 Rc7 20. Rfc1 Rfc8 21. Bxa6 bxa6 22. Qxa6 Qe4 23. h3 $16) 15. Bg3 Bh4 (15... Rc8 16. h3 (16. Na4 b5 17. Nc5 Nxc5 18. dxc5 e5 19. Bf5 Rc7 20. Rfd1 $16) 16... Nb6 17. Rc2 Bd6 $14) 16. Bxh4 Qxh4 17. Rc2 Rac8 18. Rfc1 Ne7 19. Na4 Rxc2 20. Rxc2 Rc8 21. g3 Qf6 22. b4 $14) (9... Bd6 $5 {Black is once again threatening to capture on f4 and force White to recapture exf4.} 10. f3 (10. Bxd6 $5 {Capturing on d6 is also playable.} Qxd6 11. O-O O-O 12. Na4 $14) 10... Bh5 11. O-O O-O 12. Na4 {White wants to postpone Bxd6 since Nd7 is not possible because the bishop on d6 will become undefended.} Bg6 13. Nc5 $14 {Including Bxg6 first is also possible.}) (9... Nh5 $6 {Black is threatening to play Nxf4 where it would force exf4 which is not in White's favor, however, White has a proper reply.} 10. f3 $1 Nxf4 11. Nxf4 g5 12. Nfe2 $14) 10. O-O $1 O-O (10... Bxe2 11. Qxe2 $14) (10... Bh5 11. Na4 Bg6 12. a3 $14) 11. Na4 $5 (11. f3 Bh5 12. Na4 Nd7 13. Qb3 $1 Ra7 (13... Na5 $6 14. Qc2 Rc8 15. Bxh7+ Kh8 16. Qxc8 Qxc8 17. Rxc8 Rxc8 18. Bd3 $16 b5 19. Nac3 Nc4 20. b3 $1 Nb2 (20... Na3 21. Rc1 $16) 21. Bb1 Bb4 (21... b4 22. Nd1 Nxd1 23. Rxd1 $16) 22. Rc1 $16) 14. Bg3 Bg6 15. Nf4 Bxd3 16. Nxd3 Qa5 (16... Bh4 $6 17. Bxh4 Qxh4 18. Nac5 Nxc5 19. Nxc5 Qe7 20. Rf2 $1 Rc8 21. Rfc2 $16) 17. Rf2 $1 Rc8 18. Rfc2 h6 19. Nac5 (19. a3 $14) 19... Nxc5 20. Nxc5 Bxc5 21. Rxc5 $16) 11... Nd7 12. a3 Bh5 13. Bg3 {With the typical idea to meet 13...Bg6 with 14.Nf4 and recapture on d3 with the knight, from where the knight will be well-placed.} Bg6 14. Nf4 Bxd3 15. Nxd3 $1 *

