1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 Nc6 5. e3 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bf5 7. Qb3 Na5 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qc2 e6 10. Bd3 {10.Nf3 is also good.} Rc8 (10... Nc6 11. a3 Nh5 12. Be5 (12. Bg3 {Bg3 in this position is also good and it's an exception to the rule to reply with Be5 when Nh5 is played.} Nxg3 13. hxg3 g6 14. f4 {Developing with 14.Nf3 is good enough for a small advantage, but this move is more ambitious.} Bg7 15. g4 {This move is preferred by the computer, although 15.Nf3 is playable.} h6 16. Nf3 Rc8 17. Kf2 {White is better in this position, and if Black castles, it may run into g5 at some point when h6-h5 can be replied with g2-g4 after some preparation from White.}) 12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 {White is threatening g4 since the knight on h5 doesn't have any escape squares.}) 11. Nf3 b5 (11... Nc4 12. O-O {This is the most natural move, but White should always consider Bxc4 when Black jumps on c4, although in this position White had already spent a tempo developing the bishop to d3 first.} (12. Bxc4 Rxc4 13. Ne5 Rc8 14. Qb3 Qb6 15. Qxb6 axb6 $14)) (11... Be7 12. O-O {12.h3 in order to retreat the bishop to h2 in case of Nh5 is also possible.} Nh5 13. Be5 Nc6 14. a3 Nf6 15. Qe2 {It's time to move the queen from the c-file.} O-O 16. Rac1 $14) 12. a3 Be7 13. Ne5 Nc4 14. Qe2 {Sooner or later, White needs to move the queen away from the firing range of the rook on c8.} O-O 15. O-O Nxa3 {It seems like White lost a pawn, but in fact, it's Black who is about to be a pawn down.} (15... Re8 16. a4 {This is White's idea, undermining the knight on c4!} a6 $6 17. axb5 axb5 18. Nxd7 Qxd7 19. b3 {The pawn on b5 is a target and Black loses material.} Nd6 (19... Nxe3 20. Qxe3 Rxc3 21. Bxh7+ $18) 20. Nxb5 $18) (15... Be8 16. a4 b4 17. Nb1 Nxe5 18. Bxe5 {White always recaptures with the bishop because dxe5 would block it.} a5 19. Nd2 {With Nb3 next.}) 16. Nxd7 Qxd7 17. Nxb5 Nc4 (17... Nxb5 18. Bxb5 Qd8 19. Rxa7 $16) 18. Nxa7 Ra8 19. b3 Bd6 (19... Nd6 20. Nb5 $16) (19... Nxe3 20. Bb5 Qb7 21. Bc6 Qb6 22. Ra6 Qxb3 23. fxe3 $18) 20. bxc4 Bxf4 21. Nb5 Rxa1 22. Rxa1 dxc4 23. Bxc4 Bb8 24. g3 $1 {White restricted Black's bishop even further, and with the extra pawn, White managed to convert the advantage into a full point.} Ne4 25. Bd3 Nd6 26. Nc3 g6 27. Na4 Qe7 28. Nc5 Rd8 29. Qb2 e5 30. Na6 Ba7 31. Nb4 Qb7 32. Rxa7 Qxa7 33. Nc6 Qa8 34. Nxd8 e4 35. Nb7 exd3 36. Nxd6 Qc6 1-0

