1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 Bf5 7. Qb3 Na5 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qc2 Rc8 10. Bd3 b5 11. a3 Nc4 12. Nf3 e6 13. O-O Be7 {White has several moves to choose from in this position, namely 14.Qe2, 14.Ne5, while 14. h3 seems a bit slow.} 14. Rfc1 {This doesn't seem as good as 14.Ne5 or 14.Qe2, but it's playable.} Qb6 15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. Bxe5 $1 h6 (16... O-O 17. Bxf6 Bxf6 18. Bxh7+ $16) 17. Qe2 a6 18. a4 b4 {This is a natural reaction to the move a4, however, this lands Black in a lost position immediately.} 19. a5 Qa7 20. Bxa6 $3 $18 {White has a completely winning position since the pawns are simply marching forward and they are unstoppable. This is a very typical idea where in addition, Black doesn't have any real counterplay.} bxc3 21. Bxc8 Bxc8 22. Rxc3 Ba6 23. Qc2 Bd8 24. Qa4+ Qd7 25. Qc6 Qxc6 26. Rxc6 Bb7 27. Rc2 Ba6 28. b4 Kd7 29. b5 {White's pawns can't be stopped except with a piece sacrifice from Black.} Bxb5 30. a6 Bb6 31. Rb2 Kc6 32. Rab1 Nd7 33. Rxb5 f6 34. Bg3 Ra8 35. R5b3 e5 36. dxe5 fxe5 37. Bxe5 1-0

