1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 Nc6 5. e3 Nf6 6. Nc3 Bf5 7. Qb3 Na5 8. Qa4+ Bd7 9. Qc2 Rc8 10. Nf3 e6 11. h3 $2 {11.h3 is too slow in this position.} (11. Bd3 $1 Nc6 12. a3 Nh5 13. Be5 Be7 (13... f6 14. Bg3 $14) 14. O-O f6 15. Bg3 f5 16. Be5 O-O 17. Rfc1 g5 18. Qd1 g4 19. Ne1 Nxe5 20. dxe5 $14) 11... a6 $2 {This move might be a waste of time in this position.} (11... Ne4 $1 $15) 12. Bd3 b5 13. a3 Be7 14. O-O O-O 15. Ne5 Nc4 16. Qe2 $1 Nd6 17. a4 $16 {Again, a typical move for White to break down Black's pawn structure on the queenside.} b4 (17... bxa4 $18 {White can capture the pawn on a6 or first capture the bishop on d7. At some point, White will recapture the pawn on a4 with a winning position.}) 18. Nb1 a5 19. Nd2 Nfe4 20. Nb3 {It's true that the knight on d6 is stable and well-placed, but the same can be said for the knight on b3. In fact, the knight on b3 might be even better than the knight on d6.} Be8 21. f3 Nf6 22. Nc5 Nd7 23. Nexd7 Bxd7 24. Rfc1 Bc6 25. Ba6 Rc7 26. Rc2 Bg5 27. Bg3 Be7 28. Rac1 Qa8 29. Bb5 Bxb5 30. axb5 Rcc8 31. b6 Nb7 32. Bc7 Nxc5 33. dxc5 Qc6 34. b3 Ra8 35. Ra1 Rfc8 36. Ra4 h6 37. Ra1 Kh8 38. Kh1 Kg8 39. Qd3 Bf6 40. Rac1 Bc3 41. Rxc3 bxc3 42. Qxc3 a4 43. bxa4 Rxa4 44. Qb2 Rxc7 45. bxc7 Qxc7 46. c6 Ra8 47. Qb7 Rc8 48. Qb5 Rb8 49. Qc5 Rc8 50. Qc2 g6 51. f4 Kg7 52. Qc3+ Kg8 53. h4 h5 54. g3 Rb8 55. Kh2 Rb6 56. Qe5 Qxe5 57. fxe5 Rb8 58. Kg2 Rc8 59. Kf3 Kf8 60. Kf4 Ke7 61. Kg5 Rc7 62. Rc2 Rc8 63. c7 Kd7 64. Kf6 Ke8 65. Rc6 Kf8 66. Rd6 Ke8 67. Rd8+ Rxd8 68. cxd8=Q+ Kxd8 69. Kxf7 Kd7 70. Kxg6 Ke7 71. Kxh5 Kf7 72. Kh6 Kf8 73. Kg6 Kg8 74. Kf6 d4 1-0

