1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. e3 a6 7. Bd3 Bg4 8. Nge2 e6 9. Rc1 Be7 (9... Bd6 {White should either capture the bishop on d6 or play the move 10.f3.} 10. Bxd6 Qxd6 11. Qb3 Bxe2 12. Bxe2 Rb8 13. O-O O-O 14. Na4 Nd7 15. Nc5 Nxc5 16. Rxc5 Rfc8 17. Rfc1 $14 {White has an advantage with the more active pieces and bishop versus knight. In general, if possible, White would like to avoid playing the move f3 earlier on since in a position like this one, it would create weaknesses and soften White's position.}) 10. O-O O-O 11. a3 Bh5 (11... Rc8 12. Na4 Nd7 13. b4 Bh5 14. Bg3 (14. Nc5 Nxc5 15. bxc5 $14) 14... Bg6 15. Nf4 Bxd3 16. Nxd3 Re8 17. Ndc5 Bxc5 (17... Nxc5 $6 18. bxc5 $16) 18. dxc5 h6 19. Qb3 $14) 12. Na4 {White could have also played 12. Bg3 with the idea after 12...Bg6, to play 13.Nf4, potentially threatening to capture the bishop on g6 with the knight where 13...Bxd3 will be answered by 14.Nxd3, where the knight is placed on a good square.} Nd7 13. b4 Bg6 14. Nc5 Nxc5 15. bxc5 Bxd3 16. Qxd3 b6 (16... Na5 17. Rb1 Qd7 18. Nc3 Nc4 19. Rb3 Rac8 20. Rfb1 $14) 17. cxb6 Qxb6 18. Rc3 Rfc8 19. Rb1 Qd8 20. Rbc1 {White has some pressure in the position, but Black with correct moves managed to neutralize it soon. The knight on e2 is inactive and it will take some time for the knight to contribute to the game, that's time that Black will use to consolidate.} Qd7 21. h3 h6 22. e4 Bf8 23. Bg3 dxe4 24. Qxe4 Ne7 25. Nf4 Rxc3 26. Rxc3 Rc8 27. Rxc8 Qxc8 28. Kh2 Qc6 29. Qe5 Qb7 30. a4 Qc6 31. Qa5 Qb7 32. Nd3 Nc6 33. Qc3 Qb6 34. Qc4 Nxd4 35. a5 Qa7 36. Qc8 Nf5 37. Nb4 Nxg3 38. fxg3 Qc5 39. Nc6 Kh7 40. Qxa6 Qc3 41. Nd8 Bc5 42. Qf1 Qxa5 43. Nxf7 Be7 1/2-1/2

