1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 cxd5 5. Bf4 Nc6 6. e3 a6 7. Bd3 Bg4 8. Nge2 e6 9. O-O Be7 10. Rc1 O-O (10... Nh5 11. f3 $18) 11. a3 Rc8 12. Na4 b5 13. Nc5 Bxc5 14. Rxc5 Nd7 15. Rc3 e5 16. dxe5 Ndxe5 17. h3 Nxd3 (17... Bxe2 18. Bxe2 $16) 18. Qxd3 Bxe2 19. Qxe2 d4 (19... Re8 20. Rd1 d4 21. Rc5 $16) 20. Rc5 $1 dxe3 21. Bxe3 Nd4 {The game seems to be equal, especially after White captures on d4, however, White decides to go for more and rightly so.} 22. Qh5 Ne6 23. Rxc8 Qxc8 24. Rc1 Qd7 {White has winning chances in this position because the bishop is clearly stronger than the knight, and the b5-pawn is too advanced which weakens Black's queenside, that pawn should have been on b7.} 25. Qd1 $1 Qxd1+ (25... Qe7 26. Rc6 $16) 26. Rxd1 Rd8 27. Rc1 $3 {The highlight move of the game! Because Black played b7-b5 earlier, now a complex of squares has been weakened - c6, b6, a6, and b7.} (27. Rxd8+ Nxd8 {Exchanging the rooks will probably lead to a draw since Black can set-up a fortress with the knight on c6.} 28. Kf1 Kf8 29. Ke2 Ke7 30. Kd3 Kd6 31. Kd4 Nc6+ 32. Ke4 Ke6 33. g4 g6 34. g5 Na5 $11) 27... h5 28. Rc6 a5 (28... Ra8 29. Rb6 h4 30. f4 (30. Kf1 $14) 30... g6 31. Kf2 Kf8 32. Kf3 Ke7 $6 33. Bf2 $18) 29. Rb6 Rd5 30. Kf1 g5 31. Ke2 g4 32. hxg4 hxg4 33. b3 Re5 34. Kd3 f5 35. g3 Kf7 36. Ra6 b4 37. axb4 axb4 38. Rb6 Re4 39. Rc6 Re5 40. Kc4 Re4+ 41. Kd5 Kf6 42. Rc4 Rxc4 43. Kxc4 Ke5 44. Kxb4 f4 45. gxf4+ Nxf4 46. Kc4 Nh5 47. Ba7 $1 Ke6 (47... Kd6 48. Bb8+ Kc6 49. Be5 $18) 48. Bb8 Nf6 49. Kd4 $3 Nd5 50. Bg3 Nb4 51. Kc5 Nd3+ 52. Kc4 Ne1 (52... Nb2+ 53. Kc3 Nd1+ 54. Kc2 $18) 53. b4 Nc2 (53... Kd7 54. b5 $18) 54. b5 Kd7 55. Be5 Ne1 (55... Kc8 56. Bc3 Kb7 57. Kb3 g3 58. fxg3 Ne3 59. Bd4 Nf5 60. Bf2 Nd6 61. Kb4 Ne4 62. Be1 $18) 56. Kd5 Nd3 57. Bd4 Nf4+ 58. Ke4 Ne2 (58... Ne6 59. Be3 Nc7 60. b6 Ne6 61. Kf5 $18) 59. Be5 Kc8 60. Ke3 Nc1 61. Bb2 Nb3 62. Bd4 Nc1 63. Kd2 Nb3+ 64. Kc3 Na5 65. Be5 Kd7 66. Bf4 $1 Kc8 67. Kd4 Kb7 68. Kc5 Ka7 69. Kb4 Nb7 70. Bc7 $1 1-0

