{This is an amazing game by White who managed to slowly combine play on both sides of the board. Once again, it's not a matter of memorizing concrete theory, but instead, understanding the ideas is much more important.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. e3 a6 7. Bd3 Bg4 8. Nge2 e6 9. Rc1 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Bg3 $5 (11. a3 $5 Bh5 12. Na4 Nd7 13. Bg3 (13. b4 $14) 13... Bg6 14. Nf4 Bxd3 15. Nxd3 Rc8 16. Ndc5 Nxc5 (16... Bxc5 17. dxc5 $14) 17. dxc5 $14) (11. f3 $6 Bh5 12. Bg3 Bg6 13. Nf4 Bxd3 14. Nxd3 Nd7 15. Na4 Re8 16. Nac5 Nxc5 17. Nxc5 Bxc5 18. Rxc5 Qe7 19. a3 Rac8 20. Qb3 $11) 11... Bh5 (11... Bxe2 {Here are some extra sample lines.} 12. Qxe2 Bd6 13. Bh4 Be7 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Na4 Be7 16. a3 Rc8 17. g3 ({Another possibility is:} 17. Nc5 Qc7 (17... Bxc5 18. Rxc5 Qe7 19. Rfc1 $14) 18. Nxb7 Qxb7 19. Bxa6 Qb8 20. Bxc8 Rxc8 21. Qa6 Na7 22. b4 $16) 17... Bd6 18. Nc5 Qe7 19. Rc2 $1 (19. Nxb7 Qxb7 20. Bxa6 Qd7 $6 21. Bxc8 Rxc8 22. Qa6 $16) 19... h6 20. h4 $14) 12. Na4 Nd7 (12... Bg6 13. Nf4 Bxd3 14. Nxd3 Nd7 15. Qb3 Na5 16. Qc3 Nc4 17. b3 Nd6 18. Qb2 $14) 13. a3 (13. Qb3 $5 {Is also possible.} Nb4 14. Nf4 Nxd3 15. Qxd3 Bg6 16. Nxg6 hxg6 17. Qb3 b5 18. Nc5 Bxc5 19. dxc5 $16 {19...Nb8 runs into 20.c6 with a winning position for White, but even if Black manages to establish a blockade with Nc6, White is still better due to the passed c5-pawn and potentially Bd6 where the bishop will be very strong.}) 13... Bg6 14. Nf4 Bxd3 (14... Rc8 {White has the possibility of capturing on g6 with the bishop and then playing Nd3 and Nc5 at some point (for which knight to c5 it should be calculated), or the other option is to capture on g6 with the knight.} 15. Nxg6 $1 (15. Bxg6 $5 hxg6 16. Nd3 {Black is more or less fine in this position.}) 15... hxg6 16. b4 $16) 15. Nxd3 Rc8 16. b4 (16. Ndc5 Nxc5 17. dxc5 Na5 18. b3 $14 {This is an advantage for White according to the computer since Black can hardly move.}) 16... Nb6 17. Ndc5 Bxc5 18. bxc5 Nc4 19. Rb1 N6a5 20. Nb6 Nxb6 21. Rxb6 Rc6 22. Rxc6 Nxc6 {In this game, White managed to combine pressuring the b7-pawn and slowly improving on the kingside.} 23. Qb3 (23. Bd6 Re8 24. Qb3 b5 $1 {Black has this strong move which White should be aware of when the bishop is on d6, so en passant is not possible.} (24... Qd7 25. Qb6 $16 (25. Rb1 $2 b5 {The same idea for Black again.} 26. a4 b4 27. Qd3 Qb7 $11 (27... a5 28. Qb5 $11)))) 23... Na5 24. Qb4 {It's not easy for Black to play Nc4, and even if Black does, the knight may end up being misplaced on the c4-square.} f6 25. Rb1 Rf7 26. Qa4 Nc6 27. Bd6 Qd7 28. h3 g6 29. Rb6 Na7 30. Qb4 Kg7 (30... Nc8 31. c6 $1 bxc6 32. Rb8 Kg7 33. Bf8+ Rxf8 34. Rb7 $18) 31. Bg3 Nc6 32. Qd2 Kg8 33. f3 Qd8 34. h4 Qf8 35. Qd3 Qe8 36. Rb1 Qc8 37. Qd1 Na5 38. Qd3 Nc4 39. Rb4 Qc6 40. e4 Kg7 41. a4 Rd7 42. Qe2 Kf7 43. h5 Qc8 44. Rb1 Qc6 45. Rb4 Rd8 46. e5 f5 47. Bh4 Rg8 48. hxg6+ hxg6 49. Bf6 Ke8 50. Qe1 Qd7 51. Qb1 Na5 52. Rb6 Kf7 53. Qe1 Nc6 54. Qb1 Rb8 55. Qb2 Kg8 56. f4 $3 Qc7 57. Rb3 Qa5 58. Rxb7 Qe1+ 59. Kh2 Rc8 60. Rg7+ Kf8 61. Qb7 1-0

