{This is a great and very instructive game by White.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 Nc6 5. e3 Nf6 6. Nc3 a6 7. Bd3 Bg4 8. Nge2 Bh5 9. O-O (9. Bg3 Bg6 10. Nf4 Bxd3 11. Nxd3 {White can reply with the same idea when Black plays Bh5.}) 9... Bg6 10. Rc1 e6 11. Na4 $1 {White is playing typical moves and ideas in the position. It's good to point out that White hasn't played the move f3 which would have slightly weakened White's pawn structure.} Bxd3 (11... Nb4 12. Bc7 $18) 12. Qxd3 Bd6 13. Bxd6 (13. Nc5 Bxc5 14. Rxc5 Nd7 15. Rc3 O-O 16. a3 Rc8 17. Rfc1 $14) 13... Qxd6 14. Nc5 Ra7 15. Nxb7 $3 {White could have continued improving the position with typical moves such as a3, b4, and at some point rerouting the e2-knight to the d3-square, however, this sacrifice that was shown several times, is again very strong for White.} (15. Qb3 $16) 15... Rxb7 16. Qxa6 Rc7 17. Nc3 Qd7 18. Nb5 Rc8 19. Nd6+ (19. Qxc8+ Qxc8 20. Nd6+ Kd7 21. Nxc8 Rxc8 {White is better in this position and it would be in White's favor to trade a pair of rooks. The best that Black can do is somehow to block the a and b-pawns, but then White can also start advancing on the kingside in order to create some weaknesses for Black.}) 19... Qxd6 20. Qxc8+ Nd8 21. Qc7 Qa6 22. Rc3 Qxa2 23. Ra3 Qc4 24. Rc1 Qxc7 25. Rxc7 O-O 26. Ra8 e5 27. dxe5 Ng4 28. Rcc8 Ne6 29. Rxf8+ Nxf8 30. Re8 1-0

