{This is another great example that shows the typical idea of making the Black's light-squared bishop useless. White will play on the other side, so the bishop won't be contributing to the game.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. cxd5 cxd5 4. Bf4 Nf6 5. Nc3 Nc6 6. e3 a6 7. Bd3 Bg4 8. Nge2 e6 9. O-O Bd6 (9... Bxe2 10. Qxe2 Bd6 11. Bg5 O-O 12. Rac1 Be7 13. Na4 h6 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nc5 Qe7 16. a3 Rac8 17. b4 (17. Nxb7 $5 Qxb7 (17... Nxd4 $1 $11 {Black has this move to counter White's sacrifice.}) 18. Bxa6 Qd7 19. Bxc8 Rxc8 20. Qa6 $18) 17... e5 $6 18. Nxb7 $1 exd4 19. Bxa6 Rc7 20. exd4 $16) 10. f3 {White can't avoid f3 this time so it's good to play it.} (10. Qd2 O-O 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. Ng3 Bh5 13. Nxh5 Nxh5 14. Rac1 $14) (10. Qb3 Na5 {With chances for both sides.}) 10... Bh5 11. Rc1 O-O 12. Bxd6 (12. Na4 $1 $14 {This is an improvement over the game continuation.}) 12... Qxd6 13. Na4 Nd7 14. Qb3 Qb4 15. Qxb4 Nxb4 16. Nf4 $1 Rfc8 17. a3 $1 Nxd3 18. Nxd3 Bg6 (18... b6 19. Ne5 $1 $16 Nxe5 20. dxe5 b5 21. Nb6 Rxc1 22. Rxc1 Rb8 23. Rc6 $18) 19. Ndc5 $1 Nxc5 20. Nb6 $3 {White doesn't win material, but instead, gets a very good positional advantage.} Rd8 21. Nxa8 Nd3 22. Nb6 Nxc1 23. Rxc1 $16 {White will enter with the rook on the c7-square next. The problem in Black's position is that the bishop on g6 is not contributing to the game.} f6 24. Rc7 Be8 25. Rxb7 Rd6 26. Nc8 Rd8 27. Rc7 Kf8 28. b4 Bb5 29. Kf2 e5 30. Ne7 g6 31. h4 Ba4 32. g4 Bb5 33. g5 exd4 34. exd4 fxg5 35. hxg5 Rd6 (35... Ke8 36. Ng8 $18) 36. Kg3 Bd7 37. Nc8 Bxc8 38. Rxc8+ Ke7 39. Rc7+ Ke6 40. Kf4 $1 1-0

