{In this lecture, I will try to provide a practical and easy-to-learn repertoire against the Queen's Gambit Declined. The vast majority of suggested variations are entirely based on understanding. Immediately after watching the videos and studying the PGN files, you will be able to start playing with White. After the moves} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {My suggestion is} 3. Nc3 {I like to keep the g1-knight flexible. In some of the lines, especially after 3...a6 and 3...a6, the knight can be developed via the e2-square. Opponent's who want to play Queen's Gambit Declined will usually start with} Nf6 ({In my suggested line, the move order does not matter so much. For instance, after} 3... Be7 4. Nf3 {Black should play ...Nf6 anyway since we are ready to follow with e2-e4.} Nf6 5. Bg5 {We get back to the main line.}) ({In case of} 3... a6 {my suggestion is} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 {In this way, White eliminates all the theory. In the model games, I will explain how to handle this version of the Carlsbad structure.}) ({In case of} 3... h6 {my main suggestion is similar. We play} 4. cxd5 ({My second suggestion is} 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 Bd6 6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. e3 O-O 8. c5 $14 {followed by pawn expansion on the queenside. Once again, White does not need any theoretical knowledge in order to play this position.}) 4... exd5 5. Bf4 {[%cal Ge2e3] In this line, however, I am often inclined to develop the knight via the e2-square. The reason is that our knight is heading for the f5-square via g3. After playing ...h7-h6, Black will think twice before preventing Nf5 with ...g7-g6.}) 4. Bg5 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. e3 {This is the first important crossroads in this line. Black's most ambitious continuation is} h6 {[%cal Gb7b6] followed by ...b7-b6.} ({Possible but too passive is} 6... Nbd7 {In this lecture, I explain how White should handle the position arising after} 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bd3 c6 9. Qc2 Re8 10. O-O Nf8 11. h3 $14) 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. Rc1 $1 {[%cal Gf1d3,Ge1g1] This is the starting position of my suggested setup. White is ready to complete the development by means of Bd3 followed by 0-0. The move 8.Rc1 is designed to prevent the advance ...c7-c5. Black's main problem is the development of the light-squared bishop. The main move is} ({As an additional option I suggest} 8. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh2h4,Gg2g4] followed by 0-0-0 and a kingside attack. This line is perfectly playable as well.}) 8... c6 ({In case of} 8... b6 {White should start with} 9. Be2 {Only after} Bb7 {we can play} 10. cxd5 {Remember, we take on c5 only when the opponent's light-squared bishop had been committed to b7.} exd5 11. b4 $14 {Another typical move. White not only prevents the advance ...c7-c5 but also threatens to fix Black's queenside structure by means of b4-b5. In my comments to the model games, you will see why White is slightly better in this structure.}) 9. Bd3 Nd7 10. O-O dxc4 {This is the most logical move. Black is planning to free himself by striking in the centre either with ...c6-c5 or ...e6-e5. As you will see in the model games, the alternatives are inferior.} 11. Bxc4 e5 {This is the main move.} ({In the endgame arising after} 11... c5 12. Ne4 cxd4 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. Nxd4 $14 {[%cal Gc4e2,Gf2f4,Ge2f3] White enjoys a risk-free advantage in view of the superior activity of his pieces. Our main idea is to proceed with Be2 followed by f2-f4 and Bf3, thus putting a Catalan type of pressure.}) 12. Ne4 {This is the simplest reaction. Once again, our idea is to simplify into a slightly better endgame. A possible line is} exd4 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. Nxd4 $14 {[%cal Gf1d1,Gf2f3,Ge3e4,Gg1f2,Gf2e3] This endgame is very well explained in the model games. White enjoys a risk-free advantage in view of 2 major factors: 1) mobile pawn centre 2) Black cannot find a good square for his c8-bishop Besides the idea of gaining space in the centre with f2-f3 followed by e3-e4, White can also consider doubling his rooks on the d-file. On the other hand, Black's queenside majority is irrelevant. Advancing the pawns will only create additional weaknesses.} *

