1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Be7 {Since we are going to play Bg5 followed by Bxf6, Black's move order does not matter. He can start either with 3...Be7 or 3...Nf6.} ({For instance, after} 3... Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. e3 O-O ({Obviously,} 5... h6 {will be answered with} 6. Bxf6) 6. Nf3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. Rc1 {we get the position from the main line.}) 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 h6 {This is the most ambitious move order. Usually, the advance ...h7-h6 is connected with the idea of ...b7-b6 and ...Bb7.} ({An alternative is} 6... Nbd7 {which is also playable of course but White's play is very easy. By the way, most probably, Black will play ...h7-h6 earlier, so we will take on f6 and he cannot even get to this position! But if we get there my advise is to take on d5 either immediately or after a move like Rc1 or Qc2.} 7. cxd5 $5 ({Another possibility is} 7. Rc1 $5 h6 8. Bh4 b6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 Bb7 11. O-O c5 12. Bf5 $14 {We see a typical structure that is usually favourable for White. Whenever White is well prepared, he can force the transition into a position with doubled pawns by means of dxc5.}) ({The position arising after} 7. Qc2 h6 8. Bh4 c6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 $14 {is similar to the main line.}) 7... exd5 {A typical position with Carlsbad structure has arisen.} ({The same structure can be reached also after} 7... Nxd5 8. Bxe7 Qxe7 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Bd3 c6 {We know that in this position, White's classical plan is to carry out a minority attack by means of b2-b4-b5 followed by ...bxc6. On the other hand, Black tries to display activity on the kingside and along the semi-open e-file. Another typical idea for him is to put a knight on d6 after exchanging the light-squared bishops. Since two pairs of minor pieces have been already exchanged, a kingside attack is not a realistic scenario. Also, it's not clear how Black can exchange the light-squared bishops. Let's take a look at the following sample line} ({In case of} 10... c5 $6 {, we should answer with} 11. dxc5 $1 ({A typical mistake would be} 11. O-O $2 {when after} c4 $15 {the advance of Black's queenside pawns is quite annoying.}) 11... Nxc5 12. Be2 $14 {In this typical IQP position, White is playing for two results.}) 11. O-O Nf6 12. Qc2 g6 13. h3 Be6 {Since Black didn't manage to exchange the light-square bishops, White has an advantage. An interesting idea would be} 14. Qc5 $5 {After an eventual exchange, White wants to free the d4-square for the knight.} ({Another possibility would be} 14. Rfc1 $5 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4,Gb4b5] planning to prepare the minority attack by means of Rab1 followed by b2-b4-b5.})) 8. Bd3 Re8 9. O-O c6 10. h3 Nf8 11. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4,Gb4b5] White has a small but stable advantage in this position. He is ready to proceed with Rab1 followed by b2-b4-b5. Black cannot exchange his problematic light-squared bishops. One of the points behind the move h2-h3 was to prevent the idea ...Bg4-h5-g6.}) 7. Bxf6 $1 {This rare line is my suggestion. Remember that we should take on f6 before Black plays ...Nbd7. In this line, the play is going for 2 results!} Bxf6 8. Rc1 $1 {This is the positional line! With his last move, White anticipates the advance ...c7-c5 which can now be answered with dxc5. Another interesting line is 8.Qd2!? followed by 0-0-0 and a very active play! Surprisingly, even after 8.Qd2, the theory is not so important.Typical ideas matter! Even though 8.Qd2 is not my main recommendation, I have provided some model games that you can check if you are interested.} c6 {This is the move that you will get in most of your games.} ({Another option is} 8... b6 {when we should start with} 9. Bd3 $1 ({or} 9. Be2 $1) 9... Bb7 10. cxd5 {Remember that this move should be played only when the black light-squared bishop has committed to b7!} exd5 11. b4 $1 $14 {Another important move. White not only prevents the advance ...c7-c5 but is also ready to fix Black's queenside with b4-b5. The problematic b7-bishop makes Black's position slightly worse.}) 9. Bd3 Nd7 10. O-O {We have reached the main tabiya of our variation. Black's main strategic problem is the passive c8-bishop. If he does nothing concrete, White can improve the position by means of Qe2 followed by Rfd1 and e3-e4.} dxc4 {This is the main continuation. The idea is to follow with ...e6-e5.} ({Many of your opponents will play} 10... b6 $6 {which is a bad move. The most precise way of punishing it is} 11. cxd5 $1 $16 (11. Qa4 $16 {is also playable.}) 11... exd5 {The most natural recapture. Black wants to proceed with ...Bb7 followed by ...c6-c5.} ({In case of} 11... cxd5 {I like} 12. Qe2 $3 $16 {[%cal Ge3e4] preparing the advance e3-e4.} ({Another important type of position arises after} 12. Nb5 $5 Bb7 13. Nd6 Qb8 14. Nxb7 Qxb7 {This position is not equal at all in view of the weak light squares in Black's camp. For instance, White can play} 15. Qa4 a6 16. Qc6 {with an obvious advantage.}) 12... a6 ({In case of} 12... Bb7 13. Nb5 $16 {White has a huge advantage.}) 13. e4 $3 $16 {This is the point behind 12.Qe2.} Bb7 ({Obviously, after} 13... dxe4 14. Qxe4 $18 {[%cal Ge4a8,Ge4h7] White is winning in view of the double attack.}) 14. e5 Be7 15. Qe3 $16 {[%cal Gc3e2,Ge2g3,Gg3h5] This French type of structure is obviously favourable for White. White's long-term plan is to build a kingside attack. A possible idea is to go for the manoeuvre Nc3-e2-g3. On the other hand, Black does not have constructive counterplay.}) 12. e4 $1 $16 {Just in time! White opens the position before Black manages to complete the development. The following line shows how White can develop his initiative in this type of position.} dxe4 13. Bxe4 Bb7 14. Nb5 Nb8 15. Re1 a6 16. Nc3 Nd7 17. Qc2 $16 {White has an obvious advantage.}) ({If Black plays a passive move such as} 10... Be7 {our usual idea is} 11. Qe2 {planning to proceed with Rfd1v followed by e3-e4.} Nf6 ({A typical reaction to} 11... b6 {is} 12. cxd5 exd5 ({In case of} 12... cxd5 {a good idea would be} 13. Ba6 {[%cal Gc1c2,Gf1c1] followed by doubling the rooks on the c-file. Black will face huge problems on the queenside in view of the vulnerable light squares.}) 13. e4 {Once again, White employs the familiar motif. His advantage is beyond question.}) 12. Rfd1 Bd7 13. e4 $16 {White is strategically winning.}) 11. Bxc4 e5 $1 {This is the most principled continuation. Besides attacking the centre, Black wants to open the way of his light-squared bishop.} ({The alternative} 11... c5 $5 {is a decent try for Black to free himself! Just like in the main line, my preference would be} 12. Ne4 $1 {going for a pleasant risk-free endgame.} ({It should be pointed out that after} 12. Qe2 $1 cxd4 13. exd4 Nb6 14. Bd3 g6 15. Be4 $14 {White retains some advantage in the arising position with IQP. Black still has problems with the development of the queenside. White can increase the pressure by means of simple moves such as Rfd1, Ne5, and Qf3. Also, Black should always reckon with the advance d4-d5.}) 12... cxd4 {The most straightforward continuation.} ({Dubious is} 12... Be7 $6 {in view of} 13. d5 exd5 14. Qxd5 $14 {when White is better in view of his better development and superior piece activity. Let's see what happens if Black tries to untangle by means of} Nb6 $2 ({A bit better would be} 14... Qc7 {when after} 15. Qh5 $14 {White's pressure is still very annoying.}) 15. Qxd8 Rxd8 16. Bb3 $1 {This is the point! It turns out that Black cannot defend the c5-pawn.} Bg4 (16... c4 17. Bxc4 Nxc4 18. Rxc4 Be6 19. Rc7 $16) 17. Nxc5 {Black does not have any compensation for the pawn.}) 13. Nxf6+ $1 Nxf6 {The most natural recapture.} ({Worse is} 13... Qxf6 $6 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. Nxd4 $14 {This typical endgame with symmetrical pawn structure is very difficult for Black due to the superior activity of White's pieces. Among all the other ideas, White can consider increasing the pressure by means of f2-f4 followed by Be2-f3.} a6 {Black prepares ...b7-b5. It turns out, however, that this idea does not work tactically.} ({In case of} 15... Nb6 {the most precise retreat is} 16. Be2 $1 {Our bishop will be perfectly placed on the diagonal h1-a8.} Bd7 ({It's obvious that after} 16... e5 17. Nb5 {White's superior activity gives him a huge advantage.}) 17. f4 $1 $14 {[%cal Ge2f3] This is my preferred continuation. Before putting the bishop on f3, it makes sense to gain some space.} ({The immediate} 17. Bf3 $14 {is possible as well. White retains a small edge.})) (15... Nf6 16. Be2 $1 {[%cal Gf2f4,Ge2f3] Once again, we see the same idea. White is planning to proceed with f2-f4 followed by Bf3.} Bd7 17. f4 Rac8 18. Bf3 b6 19. e4 $16 {We can now see one of the points behind the advance f2-f4. Now, Black should reckon with the annoying positional threat of e4-e5.}) 16. Rfd1 $16 {White has a huge advantage. It's important to point out that the advance} b5 $4 {does not work in view of} 17. Nxe6 $1 bxc4 18. Nxf8 Kxf8 19. Rxc4 Ke8 20. f3 $18 {when White is practically winning.}) 14. Qxd4 $1 {Even though taking with the knight is possible as well, I prefer the endgame.} Qxd4 {After the exchange of the queens, White is playing only for two results.} ({Black can deviate with} 14... Qe7 {Nevertheless, after} 15. Bb3 b6 16. Qf4 $14 {[%cal Gc1c7] White is still slightly better due to his more active pieces. Black should reckon with the threat of Rc7.}) 15. Nxd4 Bd7 {There is nothing more natural than connecting the rooks with this move.} ({Another option is} 15... b6 {Besides being a bit slow, this move also weakens the c6-square. White has many ways to develop his initiative. The most natural seems to be} 16. Bb5 {[%cal Gc1c7] preparing Rc7.} ({Another typical strategy is} 16. f3 Bb7 17. Kf2 $14 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gf2e3] planning to proceed with e3-e4 followed by Ke3. In this pawn structure, the construction f3-e4 is a typical way of restricting Black's light-squared bishop.}) 16... Bb7 17. Rc7 Bd5 ({After} 17... Rab8 {White can use the vulnerable c6-square by means of} 18. Bc6 $16) 18. a3 $14 {White is still slightly better. The following sample line shows that it's not easy for Black to neutralize White's initiative.} Rfc8 19. Rfc1 Rxc7 20. Rxc7 a6 21. Bc4 (21. Bc6 $14) 21... Bxc4 22. Rxc4 $14 {The control of the c-file as well as the vulnerable black queenside pawns provide with an advantage.}) 16. Be2 $5 ({Starting with} 16. f4 $5 {is possible as well. After} Rac8 17. Be2 Rfd8 18. Bf3 $14 {White enjoys his typical advantage.}) 16... Rac8 ({Risky is} 16... e5 17. Nf3 {when Black's development is not enough to support his overextended position. A possible follow-up would be} Bg4 18. Rc7 $16 {with a huge advantage for White.}) 17. f4 $1 {The right way of handling the position.} Rfd8 ({Exchanging all the rooks does not help Black since after} 17... Rxc1 18. Rxc1 Rc8 19. Rxc8+ Bxc8 {White can play} 20. Nb5 $18 {winning a pawn.}) 18. Bf3 b6 19. Kf2 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gf2e3] An important positional move. White wants to follow with e3-e4 and Ke3.} Kf8 20. e4 $16 {[%cal Gf2e3,Ge4e5] White is going to continue with e4-e5 and Ke3.} g5 21. g3 Ke7 22. e5 Ne8 23. Ke3 $16 {This natural move is good enough.} ({Another typical idea would have been} 23. fxg5 hxg5 24. h4 $16 {creating a distant passed pawn.}) 23... gxf4+ 24. gxf4 {White managed to convert his obvious advantage in the game Livaic - Markidis, 2017.}) ({The move} 11... Nb6 $2 {is a very bad positional move, typically played by inexperienced players! The knight is stepping away from the important squares c5 and e5. Now Black is unable to break in the centre. After the simple} 12. Bb3 Nd5 13. Ne4 $16 {White has a huge advantage.}) ({Playing in the Meran style with} 11... b5 $2 12. Bd3 a6 {[%cal Gc8b7,Gc6c5] does not work since Black cannot carry out the advance ...c6-c5. For instance, the position arising after} 13. Ne4 Bb7 14. Bb1 $16 {Is very difficult for Black because he is deprived of counterplay. A possible follow-up would be} Be7 15. Qc2 g6 16. Rfd1 Rc8 17. Ne5 $18 {with a strategically winning position for White.}) 12. Ne4 $1 {Once again, this typical move provides us with a safe advantage.} exd4 13. Nxf6+ {Regardless of how Black takes on f6 we are going to take on d4 with the queen. I believe that in the arising endgame positions White enjoys a risk-free advantage.} Qxf6 ({Nothing changes} 13... Nxf6 14. Qxd4 $5 Qxd4 ({Black can also try} 14... Bg4 {The problem is that after} 15. Qxd8 Raxd8 16. Ne5 {we see that the bishop is vulnerable on g4. A possible continuation would be} Bh5 17. f4 Nd7 18. Nxd7 Rxd7 19. h3 $14 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gf4f5] White is better in view of the annoying threat of g2-g4 followed by f4-f5.}) 15. Nxd4 Bd7 16. f3 $16 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gf1d1] White has an advantage in this typical endgame because of his better bishop and mobile majority. His next moves will be Rfd1 and e3-e4. If Black starts advancing his queenside pawns, he will only create weaknesses.}) 14. Qxd4 $1 Qxd4 15. Nxd4 {Now, has a choice. On the other hand, regardless of where the black knight will go, White is ready to restrict it.} Nf6 {Black chooses a stable square for his knight.} ({The best response to} 15... Ne5 {is} 16. Be2 $1 $16 {restricting the knight. The play might continue} Bd7 17. Rfd1 Rfe8 18. Rd2 $16 {After doubling the rooks on the d-file, White is ready to start advancing his kingside majority. If Black plays} Rad8 {it makes sense to start with} 19. b4 {limiting the mobility of Black's queenside pawns.}) ({After} 15... Nb6 {we play} 16. Bb3 $1 {again restricting the knight. Afterwards, our plan remains the same. The attempt to challenge the bishop by means of} a5 {is not dangerous.} ({Obviously, the IQP type of position arising after} 16... Nd5 $2 17. Bxd5 cxd5 $16 {Is favourable for White. Even if the immediate invasion on c7 wasn't possible, Black would have been doomed to passivity until the end of the game.}) 17. a3 a4 18. Ba2 $16 {The bishop is safe now. On the other hand, Black's overextended queenside might become a target.}) 16. f3 $1 {Black has a problem wth his passive c8-bishop. His queenside majority is irrelevant and, in fact, it can even become a target!} Bd7 17. Rfd1 {The most logical move. The control of the d-file is one of the most important strategic elements in this position.} ({With the black rook being on a8, I don't like the move} 17. b4 {The drawback is that after} a5 18. b5 c5 {Black gets a protected passed pawn.}) 17... Rad8 $6 {Removing the rook from a8 makes possible the advance b2-b4. Maybe, putting the other rook on d8 would have been a better idea.} ({As always, the advance} 17... c5 {only creates new weaknesses. A possible line would be} 18. Nb5 $16 Bxb5 19. Bxb5 Rfc8 20. e4 {The bishop dominates the black knight in this position. The immediate threat is e4-e5 followed by Rd7.}) 18. e4 $5 ({Even better would have been} 18. b4 $16 {with a nearly decisive advantage!}) 18... Rfe8 19. b4 $1 {Better later than never!} Bc8 20. Bb3 $1 {Good prophylactic move. Besides sidestepping all ...Nxe4-based ideas, White can also consider the advance b4-b5.} ({Even after} 20. Kf2 {the "tactics" arising after} Nxe4+ $2 21. fxe4 Rxe4 {don't work in view of} 22. Nb3 $16) 20... a6 21. Kf2 g6 22. Ne2 Be6 23. Bxe6 fxe6 24. Nf4 $3 {This move marks the beginning of a very deep positional idea.} Kf7 25. Nd3 Nd7 26. Nb2 Nb6 27. a4 $1 {An important positional move. After fixing the queenside by means of a4-a5, White is planning to follow with Na4-c5.} Ke7 28. a5 Rxd1 29. Rxd1 Nd7 30. Na4 $3 {[%cal Ga4c5]} Rf8 ({The pawn endgame arising after} 30... Rc8 31. Rxd7+ $3 Kxd7 32. Nb6+ Kc7 33. Nxc8 Kxc8 {is totally winning for White. For instance, after} 34. Ke3 Kc7 35. Kd4 Kd6 36. e5+ Kd7 37. Kc5 Kc7 38. f4 $18 {Black will soon be in a zugzwang.}) 31. Nc5 $3 Nxc5 32. bxc5 $18 {The endgame was reached in the game Gligoric - Filip, 1965. White is technically winning. Gligoric converted his advantage without any trouble.} Rf7 33. Ke3 Kf6 34. h4 $1 h5 35. Kf4 $3 e5+ 36. Ke3 Kg7 37. g3 Re7 38. f4 exf4+ 39. gxf4 Kf6 40. Rd6+ Kg7 41. e5 Kf7 42. Ke4 Kg7 43. f5 gxf5+ 44. Kxf5 *

