{This excellent game shows that even with queens on the board, Black's position is not easy to handle.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 {Black cannot proceed without this move. Otherwise, White will play e2-e4.} ({For instance, after} 4... c6 5. e4 dxe4 6. Nxe4 Nf6 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Bd3 {White is better.}) 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1 c6 ({Note that in your games, you might often face moves such as} 8... Nc6 {The problem is that after a simple move like} 9. a3 {Black does not have the possibility to free himself. Note that the knight is poorly placed on c6. The c7-pawn cannot fight for the centre.}) {The next couple of moves are theoretical and don't need explanations.} 9. Bd3 Nd7 10. O-O dxc4 11. Bxc4 e5 12. Ne4 exd4 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 ({We already know how to handle the endgame arising after} 13... Qxf6 14. Qxd4 Qxd4 15. Nxd4 $14) 14. Nxd4 {Even though my preference would be to take with the queen, this move is playable as well.} Qe7 15. Qb3 $1 {[%cal Gf1d1] After this precise move, it becomes clear that there are no comfortable squares for the black bishop. At the same time, White is ready to proceed with Rfd1.} Rd8 16. Rfd1 Nd5 {The idea of this move is to play ...Nb6 at some point. Objectively speaking, however, it's difficult to point out a constructive idea for Black.} ({Traditionally, the move} 16... c5 {only creates additional weaknesses. White can play} 17. Ne2 Bf5 18. Nf4 $14 {immediately heading for the important d5-square.}) ({The move} 16... Rb8 $4 {does not work tactically in view of} 17. Nxc6 $18) ({Useless is} 16... Bg4 $6 17. f3 Bh5 18. e4 $14 {when White manages to establish his strong centre. At the same time, the black bishop is totally useless on h5.}) 17. Be2 $1 $14 {I like this move. White is playing against the c8-bishop. Additionally, the bishop can put pressure via the f3-square.} ({Another idea would have been} 17. Rd2 $5 $14 {preparing to double the rooks.}) 17... a5 {As we have already discussed, this advance makes Black's queenside structure less flexible. We should only prevent the idea ...a5-a4-a3.} 18. a3 $1 a4 19. Qc4 Nb6 20. Qc5 Qxc5 21. Rxc5 {Once again, we have reached this typical endgame with a slight advantage for White. Ivanisevic managed to win this position in a nice style.} Bd7 22. h4 $5 (22. f3 $14 Nd5 23. Kf2) 22... Be8 23. f4 $1 Rd5 24. Rxd5 Nxd5 25. Kf2 $14 Nf6 26. Nf5 c5 27. Bf3 Rb8 28. e4 Bd7 (28... Bc6 29. Ne7+ $18) 29. Nd6 h5 30. f5 $3 $18 Bc6 31. e5 $1 Ng4+ 32. Bxg4 hxg4 33. Kg3 Kf8 34. Kxg4 Bxg2 35. f6 $3 gxf6 (35... g6 36. Rd2 {[%cal Gh4h5]}) 36. exf6 Rd8 37. Kf4 Kg8 38. Ke5 Kh7 39. Rg1 Rg8 40. Nxf7 Rg4 41. Kf5 Rg3 42. Ng5+ 1-0

