{This game is another example of how White can create problems for Black with queens on the board.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 {Obviously, this is not our move order. In this exact position, Black can play moves such as 4...dxc4, 4...c6, and 4...Bb4, and 3...c5.} ({In this case, I would play} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Qc2 {as I suggest in my bonus lecture.}) 4... Be7 5. Bg5 {Now, we reached our usual line.} h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1 c6 9. Bd3 dxc4 10. Bxc4 Nd7 11. O-O e5 12. Ne4 exd4 13. Nxd4 {Even though I suggest 13.Nxf6, this move does not change the character of the game. Black cannot save his dark-squared bishop anyway.} Nb6 ({In case of} 13... Be5 {, White will play} 14. f4 {forcing Black to part with his dark-squared bishop.}) 14. Nxf6+ Qxf6 15. Bb3 {An important move. When the black knight is on b6, we are going to restrict it be retreating the bishop on b3.} Bd7 16. Qd2 $5 {An interesting move. Depending on what Black plays, the white queen can go either to b4 or a5.} ({Another very insteresting idea is} 16. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5] planning to expand with a4-a5. Black is forced to respond with} a5 {after which his queenside structure loses flexibility. One may argue that the b4-square is weak now, but the black knight can never reach it. Additionally, White can make use of the unstable b6-knight by means of} 17. Qc2 Rfd8 18. Qc5 $14 {Black's position is practically very difficult.}) 16... Rad8 ({As always, the move} 16... a5 {gives nothing. After} 17. a3 Rfd8 18. Qc3 $14 {White retains his usual advantage.}) 17. Qb4 {[%cal Ga2a4,Ga4a5] White is preparing the advance a2-a4-a5.} ({Another interesting option would have been.} 17. Qa5) 17... Rfe8 18. a4 {White's advantage is obvious. After} Bc8 19. Qa5 Nd5 20. Bxd5 Rxd5 21. Qxa7 {he won a pawn and the game.} Qg5 22. Qb8 Red8 23. Qg3 Qe7 24. Qf4 Qb4 25. b3 c5 26. Nb5 Qxb3 27. h3 b6 28. Qc7 Ba6 29. Qxb6 Bxb5 30. axb5 c4 31. Rb1 Qa2 32. Qc7 R5d7 33. Qc5 Rd2 34. e4 c3 35. Ra1 Qb3 36. Ra3 Qb2 37. Rxc3 Rd1 38. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 39. Kh2 g6 40. Rf3 Qa1 41. Qe7 Rh1+ 42. Kg3 Qa2 43. Qe8+ Kg7 44. Qe5+ Kg8 45. Rd3 Rd1 46. Rxd1 1-0

