{Another very interesting endgame by the famous GM Krasenkow!} 1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3 O-O 8. Rc1 c6 ({Let's suppose that Black decides to develop his pieces by means of} 8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 b6 10. O-O Bb7 {In this case, White's first priority is to start playing in the centre with simple moves such as} 11. Qe2 Nd7 12. Rfd1 {[%cal Ge3e4] followed by e3-e4. Even though it's clear that White is already better, we will go a bit further. Black can try to escape the opposition along the d-file by playing} c6 13. e4 Qb8 {In this case, the most precise continuation would be} 14. e5 Be7 15. Bb3 {Remember that the main problem for Black in this position is his useless knight that cannot be activated. Whenever Black plays ...c6-c5, White will answer it with d4-d5. Also, the move ...b6-b5 with the idea of ...Nb6 will be met by Ne4. In this case, the b7-bishop will remain out of play until the end of the game.}) 9. Bd3 Nd7 10. O-O dxc4 11. Bxc4 e5 12. Ne4 exd4 13. Nxf6+ Nxf6 14. Qxd4 {We are already familiar with this theoretical position. In this game, instead of immediately going for an endgame, Black played} Qe7 {It turns out, however, that after the precise} 15. Qe5 $1 {White gets his typical endgame advantage anyway.} Qxe5 {Black has nothing better than exchanging queens.} ({In case of} 15... Be6 16. Bxe6 fxe6 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 18. e4 $14 {White has an obvious advantage in view of his superior pawn structure and the vulnerable black king.}) 16. Nxe5 $14 Be6 17. Bxe6 fxe6 {This endgame is very problematic for Black, especially if White manages to play f2-f3 followed by e3-e4.} 18. Rfd1 {There is nothing more natural than occupying the only open file.} ({Nevertheless, I would have started with} 18. f3 $1 {[%cal Ge3e4] immediately creating the positional threat of e3-e4. Let's take a look at a sample line:} Rfd8 19. e4 Rd4 20. Rfd1 Rad8 21. Rxd4 Rxd4 22. Kf1 {It turns out that Black's control of the d-file is only temporary. The white king will soon occupy the e2-square.} Rd2 23. Nc4 Rd8 24. Ke2 Kf8 25. Na5 {The most straightforward continuation. In such positions, the a5-knight often immobilizes Black's queenside.} ({Another good positional move would be} 25. b4 {gaining space and fixing the queenside structure.}) 25... Rd7 26. Rd1 $1 {White uses Black's vulnerable queenside to take control of the d-file. Black cannot accept the exchange of the rooks. The game might continue} Rc7 27. Rd8+ Ke7 28. Rb8 b6 29. Nc4 Nd7 30. Rg8 Kf7 31. Ra8 {with a huge advantage for White. Black is doomed to passivity.}) ({Another idea is} 18. Nc4 {[%cal Gc4a5] planning to follow with Na5.}) 18... Rfd8 19. f3 Rd5 20. Ng6 Kf7 21. Nf4 Rb5 22. Nd3 Ke7 23. e4 $14 {Again, White is slightly better. It transpires that the b5-rook is rather problematic. Later on, Krasenkow managed to convert his advantage.} Rd8 24. b3 Nd7 25. Kf2 a5 26. Ke2 Ra8 27. Nb2 Nb6 28. Nd3 Nd7 29. Nb2 Nc5 30. Nc4 Nd7 31. Nb2 e5 32. Rd2 Rc8 33. Nc4 Rc7 34. Rcd1 Rc5 35. Ne3 g6 36. Rd6 Nf8 37. Rd8 Ne6 38. Rh8 Nd4+ 39. Kf2 h5 40. Rh7+ Kd6 41. Rh6 Rg7 42. Nf5+ Ke6 43. Nxg7+ Kf7 44. Nxh5 Rc2+ 45. Kf1 gxh5 46. Rxh5 Rxa2 47. Rxe5 Nxb3 48. Rd7+ Kf6 49. Rf5+ Ke6 50. Rxb7 a4 51. Rh5 Nd2+ 52. Ke1 a3 53. Ra7 Kd6 54. Ra4 Nb3 55. e5+ Kd5 56. f4 Nd4 57. e6+ Ke4 58. e7 1-0

