{Now, I would like to provide a sharp alternative to my main recommendation against QGD. After the moves} 1. d4 e6 2. c4 d5 3. Nc3 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bxf6 Bxf6 7. e3 O-O {White can also play} 8. Qd2 $5 {[%cal Ge1c1,Gh2h4,Gg2g4,Gg4g5] The idea is very simple. White is planning to castle long and start attacking on the kingside by means of h2-h4 and g2-g4-g5. Practically speaking, playing this position with Black is not very comfortable. As a matter of fact, White even does not need to know a lot of theory in order to play this line. What matters is good calculation!} c6 $6 {This is too slow. White can already start attacking.} 9. h4 $3 Nd7 10. g4 {Since White can castle whenever he wants, we can consider his king rather safe. For the moment, he wants to speed up the attack.} g6 $2 {This is already a step in the wrong direction. Black further weakens his kingside.} ({A bit better would have been} 10... Be7 {planning to meet g4-g5 with ...h6-h5. White's best continuation seems to be} 11. Qc2 $1 $36 {It's very important that after} a6 12. O-O-O b5 13. c5 $16 {closing the queenside and gaining space. Black does not have any counterplay whatsoever.}) 11. g5 $3 $16 {A very strong pawn sacrifice. White wants to open the kingside as soon as possible.} hxg5 ({After} 11... Bg7 {White can play either} 12. h5 ({or start with} 12. gxh6 Bxh6 13. O-O-O)) 12. hxg5 Bg7 ({Accepting the sacrifice with} 12... Bxg5 {is very dangerous as well. After} 13. O-O-O Bf6 14. e4 $16 {White has a powerful initiative. Black will not survive for too long.}) 13. O-O-O dxc4 14. Ne4 {[%cal Gf3h2,Gh2g4,Gf2f4,Gd2h2] White does not even bother to recapture on c4. Instead, he is going for the attack. The next moves are going to be Nh2-g4 followed by f2-f4 and Qh2.} Qc7 15. Nh2 $1 b5 16. Ng4 $18 {[%cal Gf2f4,Gd2h2] White has an overwhelming attack. In the game Terrieux, K - Pogorelov, R, he won after a few moves.} f5 (16... Bb7 17. Nef6+ $18) 17. gxf6 Nxf6 18. Nexf6+ Bxf6 19. Qc2 Kg7 20. Bg2 e5 21. Nxf6 Rxf6 22. Qe4 Bf5 23. Qh4 g5 24. Qxg5+ Bg6 25. Be4 exd4 26. Rdg1 Qd6 27. Qh6+ Kf7 28. Bxg6+ Ke7 29. Qg7+ Ke6 30. Bf7+ Rxf7 *

