{In this game, we will see Black's most precise reaction to 8.Qd2.} 1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Be7 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. Qd2 a6 $5 {This is probably the best move for Black here. Even though 9.0-0-0 is still playable, in this case, it's probably wiser to switch to the plans with 0-0.} 9. O-O-O ({The computer indicates that the most precise continuation is} 9. Rd1 $1 $14 {making it very difficult for Black to carry out the advance ...c7-c5. A possible line would be} dxc4 10. Bxc4 b5 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. Be4 $14 {when White is slightly better in view of the backward c7-pawn. Once again, it will be difficult for Black to prepare ...c7-c5.}) ({Another playable option is} 9. Rc1 $14) 9... b5 $5 {This interesting move definitely gives Black counterplay.} ({A decent alternative is} 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 b5 11. Bd3 Bb7 $132 {The position is balanced. Had the white king been on the kingside, White would have enjoyed a serious positional advantage. In positions with long castle, however, our opponent has counterplay by definition.}) 10. cxd5 ({I would have played} 10. c5 {Nevertheless, the computer indicates that after} Nc6 {Black has some counterplay which is mainly based on the advance ...e6-e5.}) 10... exd5 {Black definitely has counterplay in this unclear position. Eventually, he even managed to win the game.} 11. Kb1 (11. Bd3 $5 Re8 12. Rhg1 Be6 13. g4 $132) 11... Be6 12. Bd3 Nd7 13. e4 dxe4 14. Bxe4 Rb8 15. Qf4 Nb6 16. Ne5 Qd6 17. Bc2 Nd5 18. Qe4 Nxc3+ 19. bxc3 Rfe8 20. Qh7+ Kf8 21. Rhe1 Bxe5 22. Rxe5 f6 23. Rxe6 Qxe6 24. f3 b4 25. c4 Rbd8 26. c5 Qg8 27. Qf5 Qd5 28. Qh7 Re3 29. Kb2 Rde8 30. Qg6 Ra3 31. Bb3 Rxb3+ 32. axb3 Re2+ 0-1

