{In the following example, Black plays ...b7-b6 but delays ...Bb7.} 1. c4 Nf6 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nf3 d5 4. d4 Be7 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 h6 7. Bxf6 Bxf6 8. Qd2 b6 {This is one of the moves that you will often face in your games.} ({The straightforward} 8... c5 $6 {should be met by} 9. cxd5 cxd4 10. Nxd4 exd5 11. Bb5 $3 $14 {Remember this key move. The idea is to prevent Black from putting pressure on the centre by means of ...Nc6.} ({The alternative} 11. Be2 {is rather slow. After} Nc6 12. O-O ({In case of} 12. Nxc6 bxc6 $132 {[%csl Gc8,Gf6][%cal Ga8b8,Gb8b2] the bishop pair as well as the semi-open b-file provide Black with excellent dynamic possibilities.}) 12... Nxd4 13. exd4 Be6 $132 {Black enjoys comfortable equality.}) 11... a6 ({After} 11... Bxd4 12. Qxd4 Nc6 {White can obviously take the pawn by means of} 13. Qxd5 {when Black does not have enough compensation.} ({Nevertheless, even after} 13. Bxc6 bxc6 14. O-O $14 {White enjoys a classical advantage.})) ({An interesting subtlety is that} 11... Qd6 {is best answered with} 12. Rc1 $1 ({After} 12. O-O Nc6 $132 {Black has some counterplay.}) {The idea is that} 12... Nc6 $2 {runs into} 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Ne4 Qe6 15. Nxf6+ Qxf6 16. Bxc6 $18 {with a winning advantage for White.}) 12. Ba4 b5 13. Bb3 $16 {White has a huge advantage since Black does not have any compensation for his inferior structure.}) 9. O-O-O Nc6 $6 {In my opinion, this is a dubious move since it does not contribute to Black's counterplay.} ({In case of} 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 Bb7 {White can already start with} 11. h4 {[%cal Gd2e2,Ge3e4] followed by Qe2 and e3-e4. It's very difficult for Black to create counterplay in this position.} Nd7 $6 12. Qc2 Qe7 ({The problem is that whenever Black plays} 12... c5 $2 {the answer will be} 13. d5 $16 {with a huge advantage for White.}) 13. e4 g6 14. Kb1 $36 {White has an obvious advantage in view of his strong centre and attacking potential on the kingside. At the same time, Black does not have any counterplay.}) ({We already know that the type of position arising after} 9... Bb7 10. cxd5 exd5 11. g4 Nd7 12. h4 Be7 13. Bd3 $16 {is favourable for White. Black has nothing to oppose to White's kingside attack. Note that whenever Black plays ...Bb7, it's usually time for cxd5. We can see how passive is the b7-bishop in this type of position.}) 10. h4 $16 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] Thematic and very strong. Now, Black should already reckon with the advance g2-g4-g5.} g6 {Black is trying to secure the g7-square for his bishop.} ({Let's see how White can develop his attack in case of} 10... Bb7 $2 {Once we see the bishop on b7, we start with} 11. cxd5 exd5 {And, when the centre is fixed, it's time to start attacking on the kingside -} 12. g4 g6 13. g5 {We are never afraid of sacrificing a pawn in order to open files on the kingside. After} hxg5 14. hxg5 Bxg5 15. Nxg5 Qxg5 16. f4 $18 {White is already winning since the queen is coming to h2.}) ({If Black tries to justify ...Nc6 by means of} 10... Na5 {we shouldn't bother to defend the c4-pawn. It's better to start attacking with} 11. g4 {The following line is pretty logical -} Nxc4 12. Bxc4 dxc4 13. g5 hxg5 14. hxg5 Bxg5 15. Nxg5 Qxg5 16. f4 {[%cal Gd2h2] Once again, White is winning. The next move is going to be Qh2.}) ({If tries to mechanically stop White's kingside expansion with} 10... h5 {White can play} 11. Kb1 g6 12. Rg1 {[%cal Gg2g4] preparing the advance g2-g4.}) 11. g4 {[%cal Gg4g5] Kortschnoj starts attacking. He is ready to proceed with the typical pawn sacrifice g4-g5.} Bg7 12. Rg1 ({Another good move would have been} 12. h5 g5 13. cxd5 exd5 14. Rg1 f5 15. Bb5 {winning the battle for the e5-square. After putting his knight on e5, White can break on the kingside with f2-f4.}) 12... dxc4 13. h5 g5 14. Bxc4 $36 {White is better in view of his central superiority and kingside attacking chances. Later on, Kortschoj managed to win.} Bb7 15. Qe2 Qe7 16. Kb1 (16. Ba6) 16... a6 17. Rc1 Rfd8 18. Rgd1 Nb4 19. a3 Nd5 20. Ne4 Nf6 21. Nxf6+ Bxf6 22. Bd3 c5 23. Ne5 Bxe5 24. dxe5 Rd5 25. f4 Rad8 26. Bc2 b5 27. Rxd5 Bxd5 28. Rd1 Bc4 29. Qf3 Bd5 30. Qf2 Bc6 31. Rd6 Rxd6 32. exd6 Qxd6 33. fxg5 Qe5 34. gxh6 Be4 35. h7+ Kh8 36. Qxf7 Bxc2+ 37. Kxc2 Qe4+ 38. Kd2 Qd5+ 39. Ke1 Qh1+ 40. Kd2 Qd5+ 41. Ke1 Qh1+ 42. Kf2 Qh4+ 43. Kf3 Qh1+ 44. Kg3 Qe1+ 45. Kg2 Qe2+ 46. Kh3 Qxe3+ 47. Kh4 1-0

