{[%evp 0,131,24,-25,10,-4,13,13,9,3,3,3,13,17,13,-5,-10,3,10,1,11,15,34,22,20,4,2,7,14,13,15,2,9,-5,-3,-3,-3,0,24,5,42,14,20,38,26,52,49,39,61,76,88,85,85,91,90,82,125,119,139,145,164,146,158,116,117,119,118,123,125,127,125,117,137,135,143,148,156,133,151,128,150,153,179,165,196,189,215,176,173,115,154,145,159,166,156,147,151,159,156,131,126,137,134,133,140,141,141,154,122,129,107,111,129,119,145,148,150,147,140,151,151,127,129,128,181,163,220,193,257,253,260,163,235,238]} 1. c4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 a6 $5 {This continuation is quite playable. Black introduces the idea of ...dxc4 followed by ...b7-b5. In my opinion, White's simplest reaction is} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bf4 {[%cal Ge2e3,Gf1d3] planning to follow with e2-e3 and Bd3.} Nf6 6. e3 {In this line, White usually gets a favourable version of the Carlsbad structure. The main rule in this structure is to avoid the exchange of the light-squared bishops. If we manage to avoid this exchange, it will be very difficult for Black to create counterplay. Our next move is going to be Bd3. Later on, the knight can be developed either on e2 or f3. If you want to develop the knight on f3, however, always starts with h2-h3, in order to avoid ...Bg4.} Bd6 {The most natural continuation.} ({A typical mistake would be} 6... g6 $2 {when after} 7. h3 Bg7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nf3 $16 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Ge1g1,Gb2b4] White enjoys a huge advantage since the g7-bishop is quite useless. After castling, White can start executing his minority attack on the queenside.}) ({A standard continuation is} 6... Be7 7. Bd3 O-O {when White has a choice. If we want to go for the plans based on Nf3, we should start with} 8. h3 $5 ({Another playable option is} 8. Nge2 $5 {keeping the possibility of building a strong centre with f2-f3 followed by e3-e4. A possible continuation would be} Nh5 9. Qc2 $14 h6 10. Be5 $5 ({or even} 10. O-O-O $5 {when Whtie has the initiative in both cases.})) 8... Nbd7 9. Nf3 Re8 10. O-O c6 11. Qc2 $14 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gb2b4,Ga2a4,Gb4b5] White is ready to execute his minority attack. Being unable to exchange his light-squared bishop, Black cannot easily create counterplay.}) 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Bd3 O-O 9. h3 $1 {In this position, I prefer the plan with Nf3.} ({Obviously, the alternative} 9. Nge2 Nbd7 10. Qc2 c6 11. O-O {is playable as well.}) 9... Re8 {This flexible move keeps all the options open.} ({The plan with} 9... b6 10. Nf3 c5 {seems positionally risky since White will go for hanging whenever he wants. In my opinion, the most precise reaction is} 11. b3 $1 {preventing Black from expanding on the queenside by means of ...c5-c4 followed by ...b6-b5-b4.} Bb7 ({After} 11... Nc6 {White is ready to immediately enter a position with hanging pawns by playing} 12. dxc5 bxc5 13. O-O Bb7 14. Rc1 $14 {[%cal Gc3a4] with the black knight being on c6, the c5-pawn is quite vulnerable. Black should now reckon with the annoying threat of Na4.}) 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Rc1 $14 Rfe8 14. Ne2 Rac8 15. Rc2 {[%cal Gd1a1,Gf1c1,Gd4c5]} g6 16. Qa1 $1 {Before taking on c5, White will arrange all his pieces in the perfect way. Meanwhile, Black should sit and wait.}) 10. Nf3 Nbd7 ({Obviously, after} 10... Ne4 11. Qc2 {the e4-knight is rather unstable.}) 11. O-O b6 {[%cal Gc7c5] Black goes for a position with hanging pawns.} ({After} 11... Nf8 12. Qc2 c6 {my favourite plan is} 13. Rae1 {[%cal Gf3e5,Gf2f4,Gc2f2,Gg2g4] planning to proceed with Ne5 followed by f2-f4.} ({It goes without saying that preparing the classical minority attack with} 13. Rab1 {is 100% playable.}) 13... Ng6 14. Ng5 $3 {A very deep move stopping ...Ne4 and preparing f2-f4.} Bd7 (14... h6 $4 15. Nxf7 $18) 15. Na4 $3 {Before playing f2-f4, we should prevent ...c6-c5.} ({After} 15. f4 c5 $132 {Black has sufficient counterplay.}) 15... Rad8 16. f4 $3 $16 {[%cal Ga4c5,Gb2b4,Ga2a4,Gg5f3,Gf3e5,Gg2g4] We can now see how important was the move 14.Ng5. White can now start playing on both wings.}) 12. Qb3 {The idea of this move is to answer} c5 {with} 13. Qa3 {After} Bb7 14. Rfd1 Qc7 15. dxc5 bxc5 16. Bf1 {Black had a hard time dealing with the pressure on the hanging pawns. This position was reached in the game Sonis, F - Lumachi, G, 2019. Eventually, White won the game.} Nf8 17. Na4 Ne6 18. Rac1 Ne4 19. Nd4 c4 20. Nc3 N6c5 21. b3 Nxc3 22. Rxc3 Ne4 23. Rc2 Nd6 24. Qa4 Qe7 25. bxc4 dxc4 26. Bxc4 Nxc4 27. Rxc4 Qg5 28. Nc6 Re6 29. Qa5 Qb5 30. Rc5 Qe2 31. Qd8+ Re8 32. Qd2 Qxd2 33. Rxd2 Kf8 34. Na5 Bc8 35. Nb3 Rb8 36. Rc6 Re6 37. Nd4 Re8 38. Rdc2 g6 39. Kh2 Kg7 40. Rc7 Ra8 41. R2c5 Kf8 42. a4 a5 43. Nc6 Be6 44. Nxa5 Ra6 45. Rb5 Rea8 46. Nb3 Rxa4 47. Nc5 R4a7 48. Nxe6+ fxe6 49. Rb8+ Rxb8 50. Rxa7 h5 51. Kg3 Rb4 52. f4 e5 53. fxe5 Re4 54. Kf3 Rxe5 55. e4 Rb5 56. h4 Kg8 57. Kf4 Rc5 58. e5 Kf8 59. g3 Rb5 60. e6 Rf5+ 61. Ke4 Rb5 62. Rf7+ Ke8 63. Rg7 Ra5 64. Rxg6 Ke7 65. Kf4 Ra3 66. Rg5 *

