1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 $5 4. cxd5 $5 {Just like in the 3...a6 line, a nice and simple plan is cd5, followed by Bf4 and if possible e2-e3 and Bd3 ( DONT FORGET THAT IN THE h6 LINE I ALSO SUGGEST THE PLAN WITHOUT cd5. Check out the theory and the games!} exd5 5. Bf4 c6 6. e3 Bf5 $5 {Black is the first to take over this important diagonal, howver he has some weaknesses after his ...h7-h6 move (especially the f5 square! ).} ({In case of} 6... Nf6 {White should start with} 7. Bd3 {preventing ...Bf5.} Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. Nge2 $14 {White enjoys a small advantage.} ({Just like in the line with 3...a6, it's possible to play} 9. h3 $5 O-O 10. Nf3 Nbd7 11. O-O $14 {with a typical play.})) ({The character of the position arising after} 6... Bd6 $5 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. Bd3 Nf6 {is familiar to us. As in the line with 3...a6, we have two options -} 9. h3 {planning Nf3.} ({or} 9. Nge2 O-O 10. O-O $14) 9... O-O 10. Nf3 Be6 11. O-O Nbd7 12. Qc2 $14 {Black still needs to solve some problems since he was unable to exchange the light-squared bishops.}) 7. Bd3 $5 {When Black has played ...h7-h6, the exchange of the light-squared bishops makes a lot of sense. White will try to transfer his g1-knight to f5.} Bxd3 8. Qxd3 Nf6 9. Nge2 Nbd7 10. O-O Be7 ({In my opinion, Black has no time for} 10... Nh5 {since White can immediately open the position by means of} 11. e4 $1 dxe4 12. Qxe4+ Be7 {Black should somehow complete the development.} ({Worse is} 12... Qe7 13. Qd3 $36 Nxf4 14. Nxf4 O-O-O 15. d5 {when White has a powerful initiative.}) {Now, White's best way of handling the position is} 13. d5 Ndf6 14. Qf3 Nxf4 15. Nxf4 O-O 16. dxc6 bxc6 17. Rac1 $14 {with a risk-free advantage.}) 11. Ng3 $1 {A very strong move, exploiting the drawbacks behind ...h7-h6. The knight is heading for f5. Had the pawn been on h7, Black could have played ...g7-g6 in this position.} O-O (11... g5 $2 12. Be5 $18) ({In this case, the move} 11... g6 $6 {is strongly met by} 12. e4 $1 $16 {If White manages to open the position, he will be winning. For instance, after} dxe4 13. Ngxe4 Nxe4 14. Nxe4 Kf8 15. d5 $18 {White has a decisive advantage.}) 12. f3 $16 {[%cal Ge3e4,Gg3f5] This position was reached in the game Giri,A - Sarin, N, 2022. White is ready to proceed with natural moves such as Nf5 and e3-e4. Later on, Giri managed to win the game.} c5 (12... Re8 13. e4 $1 $16 dxe4 14. fxe4 Nc5 15. Qd2 Ne6 16. Nf5 Nxf4 17. Qxf4 $16) 13. Nf5 Re8 14. Rad1 (14. Nb5 $3 $16) 14... Bf8 15. Nb5 Nh5 16. Bd6 Qb6 17. Bxf8 Rxf8 18. Ne7+ Kh8 19. Nxd5 Qc6 20. Nbc3 Rad8 21. e4 a6 22. a3 cxd4 23. Qxd4 Nhf6 24. Rf2 Nc5 25. Qe3 Nxd5 26. Nxd5 Ne6 27. Rfd2 Rd7 28. h3 Rfd8 29. Kh1 a5 30. Kh2 Qd6+ 31. g3 Qe5 32. Kg2 Rxd5 33. Rxd5 Rxd5 34. Rxd5 Qxb2+ 35. Rd2 Qa1 36. f4 Qb1 37. h4 b6 38. f5 Nc5 39. Re2 f6 40. g4 Nd3 41. g5 Ne5 42. gxh6 Qd1 43. hxg7+ Kxg7 44. Rd2 Qb1 45. h5 Kh7 46. h6 Ng4 47. Qf4 Ne5 48. Qh4 Qc1 49. Rf2 Qc6 50. Kh3 Qc3+ 51. Qg3 Qc7 52. Qg7+ Qxg7 53. hxg7 Kxg7 54. Kg3 Nc4 55. a4 Nd6 56. Rb2 Nxe4+ 57. Kf3 Nc5 58. Rxb6 Nxa4 59. Rb5 Kf7 60. Rxa5 Nb6 61. Ra7+ Ke8 62. Ra6 Nd7 63. Ra8+ Ke7 64. Ra6 *

