{[%evp 0,27,18,18,18,9,3,6,20,20,20,-14,28,39,44,32,43,23,19,13,31,19,17,17,22,8,32,52,53,50] In this example, I will provide additional option against 3...h6.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 h6 4. Nf3 Nf6 5. Bf4 $1 Bd6 6. Bxd6 $1 {This is a nice try for White. Additionally, it's very easy to learn this line.} Qxd6 7. e3 O-O 8. c5 $5 {This move indicates White's intention to expand on the queenside. The drawback is that since there is no pressure in the centre, Black can organise the break ...e6-e5.} Qe7 9. Be2 $1 {We should develop as quickly as possible.} ({Fighting for the e5-square is pointless. For instance, after} 9. Ne5 Nfd7 10. f4 Nxe5 11. fxe5 f6 $132 {Black has tremendously strong counterplay.}) 9... Nbd7 {[%cal Gc7c6,Ge6e5] Black is preparing to proceed with ...c7-c6 followed by ...e6-e5.} ({The attempt to undermine the queenside by means of} 9... b6 {does not work quite well -} 10. b4 a5 (10... Ne4 11. Qc1) 11. a3 Ne4 12. Qc1 $14 {White is keeping everything under control and he is at least slightly better.}) 10. O-O c6 11. b4 {Black will play e6-e5 but we ignore it and keep on attacking on the queenside with an interesting initiative!} e5 12. a4 $1 (12. Qc2 $5 a6 13. a4 e4 14. Nd2 Nh7 15. b5 $132) 12... e4 (12... Re8) 13. Nd2 a5 $5 14. b5 $14 {White is slightly better in this position because the queenside play is running faster.} ({Another option is} 14. bxa5 $5 Rxa5 15. Nb3 Ra7 16. a5 $132 {with a complex position.}) *

