{In this lecture, we will discuss two very important openings. The Tarrasch Defence and The Queen's Gambit Accepted I choose а practical approach - to enter risk-free endgames. I like very much choosing such lines because it saves a lot of time studying useless theory.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 (2... dxc4 {The QGA is a very serious opening, but slightly passive.} 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. dxc5 {Again, I believe that this is the simplest approach for White.} Bxc5 ({or} 7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5) 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {Leads to a tricky endgame in which White has several nasty ideas. You don't need to know any theory, just the general rules and ideas in this endgame.}) 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 (4... cxd4 $5 {This is an ambitious gambit line and the only one which doesn't allow us to enter an endgame.} 5. Qa4+ $1 Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 $1 {I believe that we should accept the challenge} Nf6 $5 (7... Nc6 $6 {This move is an inaccuracy and White easily has an advantage after it.} 8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Qd1 Bc5 10. a3 $3 {[%cal Rc1g5]}) 8. Qd1 Bc5 9. Nf3 O-O 10. e3 Nc6 {Only now, when White can't play Bg5. Black's position looks active, but White has an extra central pawn and no weaknesses. White plans to develop his pieces slowly and then exchange them.}) 5. Nf3 {This is the main line in Tarrasch. Black has two approaches:} Nc6 {The main line} (5... Nf6 {I wouldn't say I like this move} 6. Bg5 Be6 7. dxc5 {I like this simple approach, which Carlsen and Anand also chose last year. White has an easy game.}) 6. dxc5 $5 {I like this line very much because we enter a slightly better endgame almost by force.} d4 7. Na4 Bxc5 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Qd2 (9. Bd2 $5 Qxc5) 9... Qxc5 10. e3 dxe3 11. Qxe3+ Qxe3+ 12. Bxe3 $14 {Many games were played in this position. We can conclude that White's play is easier.} *

[Event "MODERN CHESS"]
[Site "Sant Ferran de ses Roques ESP"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "TARRASCH FOR WHITE"]
[Black "FULL THEORY"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "D32"]
[Annotator "GM Ioannis Papaioannou"]
[PlyCount "41"]
[EventDate "2022.04.29"]

{My approach against Tarrasch and QGA is to enter a slightly better endgame or play positions with queens off the board. The only variation where I can't find an endgame option for White is 4...cxd4} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 exd5 (4... cxd4 $5 {This old variation has become fashionable again recently.} 5. Qa4+ $1 {This is the best move for White} (5. Qxd4 Nc6 6. Qd1 exd5 7. Qxd5 Bd6 8. Nb5 Bb4+ 9. Bd2) 5... Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 {I believe the best option is to accept the sacrifice} 7. Qxd5 $1 (7. Nf3 {This move is also interesting, but I believe Black is OK after:} Nf6 8. Bg5 {This looks promising, but Black can reach equality by playing dynamically} Nc6 $1 9. Qd2 Bb4 10. a3 Ne4 $1 {The point of Black's strategy} 11. Bxd8 Nxd2 12. Kxd2 Bxc3+ 13. Kxc3 {Initially, I was very happy with White's position, but unfortunately, Black can equalize after:} Rxd8 14. e3 Ke7 $11 {[%cal Rd8c8,Rh7h5,Rh8h6]} (14... O-O 15. Bd3 Bg4 16. Nd4 Nxd4 17. Kxd4 $16)) 7... Nf6 $1 ({It takes deep analysis and understanding to realize that White is better after the natural:} 7... Nc6 $6 {If Black prematurely develops his knight to c6 , then we have this nice plan with a fast a3 followed by Bg5!} 8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Qd1 Bc5 {this is the most logical move, but White has an extra central pawn and no obvious weaknesses.} (9... Bb4 $5 10. Bd2 O-O 11. e3 Qe7 12. Be2 Rfd8 13. Qc2 Rac8 14. O-O Bg4 15. Rfd1 $16) (9... Qb6 $5 {[%cal Re8c8] Is playable, but I believe White is slightly better after:} 10. e3 O-O-O 11. Bd2 {The player who sacrifices material for the initiative must have a safe king. If both kings are not safe, the player with extra material usually has an advantage because he can return the material and take the initiative. For example:} Bf5 {looks scary, but White is totally fine and even can try:} 12. Bb5 $5 Kb8 13. Bxc6 {giving the bishop for the knight and blocking the d-file with Nd4} Qxc6 14. O-O Ne4 15. Nd4 $14) 10. a3 $3 {This is an important improvement over 10.e3. The idea is to trap the queen on b2. I analyzed many possibilities and in general, we want to play Bg5 against all of them} ({If} 10. Bg5 {then} Qb6 $15) 10... O-O $2 (10... Qe7 11. Bg5 O-O-O (11... h6 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. e3 O-O-O 14. Qc1 Rhe8 15. Be2 Kb8 16. O-O Bf5 (16... Bd6 17. Rd1) 17. Rd1 $16 {It looks like Black has compensation, but there is nothing concrete and Black's king is not safe on c8}) 12. e3 $3 (12. Qc1 $5 Bg4 13. Qf4 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Bd6 15. Qa4 $16) 12... h6 13. Nd5 Qe6 14. Bxf6 gxf6 15. Rc1 Qd6 16. b4 Be6 17. Rxc5 Bxd5 18. Bc4 Bxc4 19. Qxd6 Rxd6 20. Rxc4 $16) (10... Qc7 11. Bg5 $1 Qb6 (11... O-O-O 12. e3 Rhe8 13. Qc1 Ne5 14. Be2 Bc6 15. Nxe5 Qxe5 16. Bf4 Qe6 17. b4 $18) 12. e3 Qxb2 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Na4 $18) (10... h6 11. Bf4 (11. b4 Bb6 12. Bb2 $16) 11... Qb6 12. e3 Qxb2 $2 13. Na4 $18) (10... Qb6 11. e3 $16 {[%cal Rc3a4]}) 11. Bg5 $1 $16 {and if} Qb6 (11... Be7 12. e3 Qb6 13. Bc4 $1 (13. Qc2 $2 Bf5) (13. Bd3 {is also possible} Qxb2 14. Na4 $18) 13... Rfd8 14. Bxf6 Bxf6 15. Nd5 Qxb2 16. Ra2) 12. e3 $1 Qxb2 $4 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Na4 $18) 8. Qd1 $1 {I choose this move} Bc5 9. Nf3 O-O $1 (9... Qe7 10. Bg5) ({I believe that Black should avoid Nc6} 9... Nc6 10. a3 $1 O-O 11. Bg5 $16) 10. e3 {We get the position where again Black has many options. We plan to defend carefully for some moves..and develop our pieces little by little. Then we can start exchanging them and win!} (10. a3 $5 Nc6 (10... h6 11. b4 Bb6 12. e3 Qe7 13. Be2 Nc6 14. O-O Rfd8 15. Bb2 Rac8 16. Rc1 Bf5 17. Qb3 Be6 18. Qc2 $16) (10... Re8 $1 11. e3 (11. Bg5 Qb6 12. e3 Qxb2 13. Bxf6 (13. Na4 Bxa4) 13... gxf6 14. Nd5 Bc6 $132 15. Rb1) 11... Qe7 12. Be2 Nc6 13. O-O Rad8 14. Qc2 Ne5 15. Nd4 $16) 11. Bg5) 10... Nc6 11. Be2 Qe7 12. O-O {The best move appears to be:} Rfd8 ({Black can start with:} 12... Bf5 13. Nd4 $14 Bg6 (13... Nxd4) 14. Nxc6 bxc6 15. Bd2 Rad8 16. Qc1 Rfe8 17. Rd1 $14) (12... Ne5 {I don't like this idea for Black} 13. Bd2 $14 {with the idea to develop the pieces slowly} (13. Nd4 $14 {This move looks decent because White is closing the d-file and putting the knight in the centre.}) (13. Nxe5 Qxe5 14. Bf3 (14. Qc2 $2 Bc6 $15 {[%cal Rc6g2,Rc5d6]}) 14... Bc6 15. Bxc6 bxc6 16. Qe2 Ne4 17. Nxe4)) 13. Qb3 $1 (13. Qc2 $1 Ne5 (13... Rac8 14. Bd2) (13... Nb4 $14 14. Qb1 Rac8 15. e4 (15. a3 Nc6 16. b4 Bd6 17. Bb2 $14)) 14. Rd1 Rac8 (14... Bc6 15. Nd4 $16) 15. Nd4 Ng6 (15... h6 16. Bd2) 16. Qb3 (16. Bd2 $4 Bxd4 17. exd4 Qxe2 $19) 16... Be8 17. Bf1 h5 18. Bd2 Bxd4 19. exd4 Rxd4 20. Bg5) 13... Be6 (13... Bg4 14. h3 Bh5 15. Rd1 Rxd1+ 16. Qxd1 Rd8 17. Bd2 Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Ne5 19. Be2 Nd3 (19... Qd7 20. Be1) 20. Bxd3 Rxd3 21. Qc2 Qd7 22. Be1) (13... Bb6 14. Bd2 Rac8 15. Rfd1 Bg4 16. Be1 Ne5 17. Nxe5 Qxe5 18. Rxd8+ Rxd8 19. Rd1 Re8 20. Qc4 $14) 14. Qc2 {Now we set a small trap} Rac8 15. Ng5 $3 Nb4 (15... Bd7 $4 {If Black decides to keep the bishop} 16. Nd5 {Ended the game immediately}) 16. Qb1 h6 17. Nxe6 Qxe6 18. a3 Nc6 19. b4 Bd6 20. Bb2 Ne5 21. Ne4 $18 (21. Nb5 $1 Neg4 22. Nxd6 Qxd6 23. g3 $16)) 5. Nf3 {Black has a choice now between two completely different lines. 5...Nc6 and 5...Nf6} Nc6 $5 {This is the main line for Black with thousands of games in it. The main move is 6.g3 with a lot of theory. Instead, I very much like the possibility 6.dxc5 which leads directly to a risk-free endgame where White enjoys a bishop pair.} (5... Nf6 $5 {I think White is better after this move and has a very easy play.} 6. Bg5 $1 Be6 (6... cxd4 $6 7. Nxd4 $14 (7. Bxf6 $5 {It is also possible to play forced, but I can't see a reason for it} Qxf6 8. Qxd4 Qxd4 9. Nxd4 Be6 10. Ndb5 Na6 11. e3 $16 g6 12. g3 Bg7 13. Bg2 O-O 14. Bxd5 $16) 7... Be7 8. e3 O-O 9. Be2 Nc6 10. O-O Be6 11. Rc1 Rc8 12. Nxc6 bxc6 {A standard transformation from IQP pawn structure to semi-hanging pawns.} 13. Na4 Qa5 14. a3 c5 15. Qc2 c4 16. Bf4 Nd7 17. Rfd1 Rfd8 18. Rd2 Bf6 19. Bd6 $16 {½-½ (32) Esen,B-Yurtseven,M/Ankara 2018/CBM 185 Extra}) 7. dxc5 $1 {The simplest move. White is aiming for a tiny advantage and easy play. White plans to place the bishop in the "b5" square. But even if he develops it to "e2" or "d3" White still enjoys a small but long-lasting advantage.} (7. e3 {will be met with} c4 {with counterplay}) 7... Bxc5 8. e3 {White's main plan here is to stop the d5-d4 push, block the isolated pawn, and later take it.} O-O (8... Nc6 $6 9. Bb5 $1 O-O 10. O-O Rc8 $1 {This is Black's best try, but I provide several sample lines. You have different ways to handle the position} (10... h6 $2 {after this mistake, White can transform his advantage by playing:} 11. Bxf6 Qxf6 12. Nxd5 Qxb2 13. Nc7 Rad8 14. Qc1 $16 Ba3 15. Qxb2 Bxb2 16. Nxe6 fxe6 17. Rab1 $16 Ba3 18. Bxc6 (18. Bc4 {This move also gives White a clear advantage} Rf6 19. Rfd1 $16) 18... bxc6 19. Rb3 Be7 20. h3 $1 $16 {Black's pawns are very weak. The endgame is very tough for Black.} c5 21. Rc1 Rd7 22. Kf1 (22. Ne5 Rd2) 22... Rc8 23. Ke2) (10... Be7 11. Nd4 (11. Ba4 $14 Rc8 12. Bb3 Na5 13. Nd4 Nxb3 14. Qxb3 $14) 11... Nxd4 12. Qxd4 h6 13. Bh4 a6 14. Be2 $14) (10... a6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Rc1 {Is a standard play with an idea Na4-c5} (12. Nd4 {This is also possible} Bxd4 13. Qxd4 {White has a wonderful position} (13. exd4 {even this is good enough for an advantage})) 12... Bd6 13. Na4 $14) 11. Rc1 (11. Qe2 h6 12. Bh4 Be7 13. Rfd1 $14) (11. Bh4 $5) 11... Be7 (11... a6 $2 12. Bxc6 Rxc6 (12... bxc6 13. Na4 (13. Nd4) (13. Qa4)) 13. Nd4 (13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Nxd5 $16 Qxb2 15. Nd4 $3 Bxd5 16. Nxc6 Bxc6 17. Rxc5 Qxa2 18. Qd4 $16) 13... Bxd4 14. Qxd4 $16 Rc4 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Qxf6 gxf6 17. b3 (17. Rcd1 $16) (17. Rfd1) 17... Rc6 18. Ne2 Rfc8 19. Ra1 $3 $16 (19. Rxc6 bxc6 20. Rd1 c5 21. f3 $14)) 12. a3 $5 $14 (12. Ba4 $5 $14) 12... h6 13. Bh4 a6 14. Bd3 $1 $14 (14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. Qd3 Qb6 16. b4) 14... Qb6 15. b4 Rfd8 16. Na4 Qa7 17. Nc5 $1 (17. h3 $2 g5 18. Bg3 Ne4 $132) 17... Bg4 18. h3 Bxf3 19. Qxf3 Ne5 20. Qf5 Nxd3 21. Qxd3 Bxc5 22. Bxf6 gxf6 23. bxc5 Rxc5 24. Qd4 Rdc8 25. Rb1 b5 26. Qxf6 $14) 9. Bd3 $1 (9. Be2 $5 h6 10. Bh4 Nc6 11. O-O $14) 9... h6 10. Bh4 Nc6 11. O-O Be7 (11... d4 $6 12. Na4 Bb6 13. Nxb6 Qxb6 14. exd4) (11... Rc8 12. Rc1 Be7 13. a3 $14) 12. Rc1 Rc8 13. h3 $14 (13. a3 $14) 13... Re8 (13... Ne4 14. Bxe7 Qxe7 15. Ne2 $14) 14. a3 a6 15. Bb1 {1-0 FULL THEORY,P-MERGED GAMES,A/Hilversum 2011/CBM 143 Extra/[,Giannis]}) 6. dxc5 $1 d4 7. Na4 Bxc5 (7... Nf6 8. a3 (8. e3)) 8. Nxc5 Qa5+ 9. Qd2 $1 (9. Bd2 Qxc5 10. Rc1 (10. b4) 10... Qb6 11. e3 Nf6 (11... dxe3 12. Bxe3 Qxb2 13. Bc4 Qb4+ 14. Nd2 Nge7 (14... Nf6 $4 15. Bc5 Qa5 16. O-O (16. Qb3)) 15. Bc5 Qa5 16. O-O O-O 17. Qe2 Re8 (17... Qc7 18. Rfe1 Re8 19. Ne4 $18 Be6 20. Bxe6 fxe6 21. Nd6) 18. Ne4 $18) 12. Bc4 dxe3 13. Bxe3 Qb4+ 14. Bd2 $1 Qe7+ (14... Qxb2 15. Qe2+) 15. Be2 $14 (15. Qe2 Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Bg4 17. Be3 O-O 18. h3 Bxf3+ 19. Kxf3 $16 (19. gxf3 $16) 19... Ne5+ 20. Ke2 Nxc4 21. Rxc4 Nd5 22. Rd1 Nxe3 23. fxe3)) 9... Qxc5 10. e3 dxe3 (10... Nge7 $6 {this is not good enough} 11. Nxd4 Nxd4 12. Qxd4 Qxd4 13. exd4 {White will be better, even without the d4-pawn} O-O 14. Be3 $16 Be6 15. Bd3 $16 Nf5 16. Be4) 11. Qxe3+ Qxe3+ 12. Bxe3 $14 {Many games were played in this position. We can conclude that White's play is easier. I am providing you with some sample lines. Please notice the fast loss for Black in the 13.Bc4 Be6 line. This proves that things can go quickly go wrong for Black If he is not careful!} Nge7 (12... Nf6 13. Bc4 (13. Bb5 $14 O-O 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. O-O) 13... O-O (13... Be6 14. Bxe6 fxe6 15. O-O Nd5 16. Bd2 Kd7 17. Rfe1 Rhf8 18. Re4) 14. O-O Re8 15. Rfc1 Be6 16. Bb5 Bd7 (16... Bd5 17. Nd4 Nxd4 18. Bxd4 Red8 19. Be3 $14) 17. h3 Ne5 18. Bxd7 Nexd7 19. Rc7 b6 20. Rd1 Nf8 21. Ng5 Ne6 22. Nxe6 Rxe6 23. Rdc1 Nd5 24. Rxa7 Rae8 25. Bd2 Re2 26. Rd1 h6 27. Rd7 Nf6 28. Rd3 Ne4 29. Re3 Nxd2 30. Rxe8+ Rxe8 31. Rxd2 b5 32. Rd4 g5 33. Rb4 Re5 34. Kf1 Kg7 35. Rb3 f5 36. Re3 Rc5 37. Rc3 Re5 38. Rc2 Kf6 39. Rc6+ Kg7 40. a3 h5 41. b4 f4 42. f3 Re3 43. Rc5 Kf6 44. Rxb5 Rxa3 45. h4 g4 46. fxg4 hxg4 47. h5 Ra1+ 48. Ke2 Ra2+ 49. Kf1 g3 50. h6 Kg6 51.