{[%evp 0,63,19,31,23,-10,0,4,82,32,43,8,12,12,17,17,17,36,30,-15,-6,9,2,29,26,39,39,39,45,30,55,49,51,51,91,79,101,93,121,55,73,59,89,85,129,112,153,122,155,153,143,126,135,121,140,150,163,163,156,155,167,169,410,412,452,490]} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 4. cxd5 cxd4 5. Qa4+ Bd7 6. Qxd4 exd5 7. Qxd5 Nc6 8. Nf3 Nf6 9. Qd1 Bc5 ({If} 9... Bb4 10. Bd2) 10. a3 O-O 11. Bg5 Qb6 12. e3 Be7 ({I will remind you that Black can't take the pawn} 12... Qxb2 $2 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Na4 $18) 13. Bd3 Bg4 14. Qc2 h6 ({Black could play} 14... Bxf3 15. gxf3 Rac8 {White can safely castle short and enjoy the advantage of the bishop pair and the extra pawn.} 16. O-O Ne5 17. Be2 $14) 15. Bh4 Rfd8 16. O-O Bxf3 17. gxf3 Nd5 18. Nxd5 Rxd5 19. Bg3 Bf6 20. Rab1 (20. Be4 {It is also possible to return the material} Rc5 21. Qe2 Qxb2 22. Qxb2 Bxb2 23. Rab1 Bxa3 24. Rxb7 {White is much better in this endgame}) 20... Rad8 21. Rfd1 h5 22. Bh7+ Kh8 23. Rxd5 Rxd5 24. Be4 Rd7 25. h3 h4 26. Bf4 Qa5 27. Rd1 Rxd1+ 28. Qxd1 g5 29. Bh2 Kg7 30. Qd7 Bxb2 31. Qxb7 Be5 32. Bxc6 {Very nice example of converting the extra pawn on this line.} 1-0

