1. d4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} d5 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 2. Nf3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Nf6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 3. c4 {[%emt 0:00:00]} dxc4 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 4. e3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} e6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 5. Bxc4 {[%emt 0:00:00]} c5 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 6. O-O {[%emt 0:00:00]} a6 {[%emt 0:00:01] Is the main move, but White can favour a very pleasant endgame} (6... Nc6 {White can try to get a good version of IQP position.} 7. Qe2 cxd4 8. Rd1 Be7 9. exd4 O-O {We reach a typical position with an isolated pawn.} 10. Nc3 {[%cal Rd4d5]} Nb4 (10... b6 $6 11. d5 $16) (10... Na5 11. Bd3 Bd7 12. Ne5 $14 {[%cal Re2f3,Rf3h3]}) 11. Ne5 Nbd5 {[%cal Rd1d3,Rd3h3]} 12. Rd3 $14) 7. dxc5 $1 {[%emt 0:00:00]} (7. a4) 7... Bxc5 {[%emt 0:00:07]} (7... Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 {White's plan is very simple: Be2-Nb1-d2-c4 and Nf3-d2-b3, followed by f3 and e4. If Black plays b7-b5 then a2-a4 move is very annoying for him.} 9. Be2 Nc6 (9... Nbd7 10. Nbd2 O-O (10... b5 11. a4 $14) (10... b6 11. Nc4 {[%cal Rf3d4,Rd4b3]} Bb7 12. Nd4 Rc8 13. Nb3 Be7 14. f3 O-O 15. e4 b5 16. Nca5 Ba8 17. Be3 $16) 11. Nb3 Be7 (11... Ba7 12. Bd2 b5 13. Bb4 $16 Re8 14. Rac1 $14 (14. Na5)) 12. Nfd4 Rb8 13. f3 Rd8 14. e4 Nf8 15. Be3) (9... b5 {this move only creates weaknesses on the queenside} 10. a4 b4 11. Nbd2 Bb7 12. Nb3 (12. Nc4 O-O 13. b3 Nc6 14. Bb2) 12... Bb6 13. Bd2 a5 14. Bb5+ $16) 10. Nbd2 Ke7 (10... O-O 11. Ne1 Rd8 12. Nd3 Be7 13. b3 Bd7 14. Bb2 Rac8 15. Nc4 Be8 16. Bf3) 11. Ne1 {Is another nice and common idea - the knight is going to d3.} (11. Nb3) 11... Bd7 (11... Rd8 12. Nd3 Bd6 13. Nc4 Bc7 14. b3) 12. Nd3 Ba7 13. b3) 8. Qxd8+ {[%emt 0:00:02]} Kxd8 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 9. Rd1+ {[%emt 0:00:01]} Ke7 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 10. Nbd2 {[%emt 0:00:01] Let's briefly overview White's ideas. In this endgame, they are much more important than the concrete theory. 1.White's main plan is Be2,Nc4,Nb3 (via d2 or d4) 2.The other route for the kingside knight is Ne1-d3 3.White always tries to get f3-e4 followed by Be3 and Kf2 - restricting Black's pieces. 4.White quite often tries to occupy the diagonal a3-f8 by means of b3-Ba3 or Bd2-b4 5.b7-b5 is almost always met with a2-a4 break 6.After b7-b6, Black has problems finding can't a good square for the c5-bishop} Nbd7 {[%emt 0:00:02]} ({If} 10... Nc6 11. Be2 Bd7 {White should play} 12. Ne1 $3 Rhd8 13. Nd3 Bd6 14. Nc4 Bc7 15. b3 {[%cal Rc1a3]} Rac8 16. Ba3+ $16) 11. Be2 {[%emt 0:00:01]} b6 {[%emt 0:00:02]} (11... b5 12. a4) 12. Ne1 $5 {[%emt 0:00:01] as we can see, the c5-bishop will be out of squares soon.} (12. Nc4 {Is another way of handling the position} Bb7 13. Nd4 Rhd8 14. Nb3 Rac8 (14... Bd5 15. Bd2 a5 16. Nxc5 Bxc4 17. Bxc4 Nxc5 18. f3 $14) 15. Bd2 Ne4 16. Be1 (16. Nxc5)) 12... Bb7 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 13. Nd3 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Bd6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 14. Nc4 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Bc7 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 15. b3 $1 $16 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Rhd8 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 16. Ba3+ {[%emt 0:00:01]} Ke8 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 17. Nd6+ {[%emt 0:00:03]} Bxd6 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 18. Bxd6 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Ne4 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 19. Bb4 {[%emt 0:00:08]} Rac8 {[%emt 0:00:19]} (19... a5 20. Be1) 20. Rac1 {[%emt 0:00:01]} (20. f3 Nef6 (20... Nc3 $1 21. Bxc3 Rxc3 22. Rac1 Rdc8 23. Rxc3 Rxc3 24. Rc1 Rxc1+ 25. Nxc1 $11) 21. e4 $16) 20... Rxc1 {[%emt 0:00:03]} 21. Rxc1 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Rc8 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 22. Rxc8+ {[%emt 0:00:01]} Bxc8 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 23. f3 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Nec5 {[%emt 0:00:09]} (23... Nef6 24. e4 Bb7 25. Kf2) 24. Nxc5 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Nxc5 {[%emt 0:00:01]} 25. Kf2 {[%emt 0:00:02]} a5 {[%emt 0:00:04]} 26. Bc3 {[%emt 0:00:02]} g6 {[%emt 0:00:06]} (26... f6 $1) 27. e4 {[%emt 0:00:02]} (27. Bd4) 27... Ba6 {[%emt 0:00:06]} 28. Bxa6 {[%emt 0:00:02]} Nxa6 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 29. Ke3 {[%emt 0:00:01]} Kd7 {[%emt 0:00:01]} (29... h5 30. g4 hxg4 (30... h4 31. h3) 31. fxg4 Nb8 (31... g5 32. Bf6) 32. h4 Nc6 33. a4 (33. h5) 33... Kf8 34. Bd4 (34. Kd3) 34... Nxd4 35. Kxd4 Kg7 36. e5 f5 37. exf6+ Kxf6 38. Ke4 Kf7 39. Ke5 Ke7 40. h5) 30. Kf4 {[%emt 0:00:05]} h5 {[%emt 0:00:05]} (30... h6 31. Bg7 h5 32. g4 hxg4 33. fxg4 Nb4 34. h