{A very good game by White ! ..try to remember the way he develops his pieces! In this endgame, the plans that matter..and not concrete theory!} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. c4 dxc4 4. e3 e6 5. Bxc4 c5 6. O-O a6 7. dxc5 Qxd1 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nbd2 b6 (9... b5 10. Be2 Bb7 11. a4 b4 12. Nb3 Nbd7 (12... Be7 13. Na5 Bd5 14. Ne5 O-O 15. f3 Bd6 16. Nec4 Bc5 17. Kf1 $16 Bxc4 18. Nxc4 a5 19. e4) 13. Nfd4 O-O 14. f3 Rfd8 15. e4 $3 e5 16. Nxc5 Nxc5 17. Nf5 Nb3 18. Rb1) 10. Be2 Bb7 11. Nc4 {White's plan is Be2-Nbd2-Nc4-Nd4-Nb3! If black goes b5 we go a4! White is always better if he gets f3-e4 followed by Be3 and Kf2} Nbd7 12. Nd4 O-O 13. Nb3 Be7 14. f3 a5 15. e4 a4 16. Nd4 Bc5 17. Be3 Rfd8 18. Kf2 Kf8 19. Nb5 Ke7 20. Bxc5+ bxc5 21. Nc3 Ba6 22. Rac1 Bxc4 23. Bxc4 Ne5 24. Be2 Rdb8 25. Rd2 g5 26. g3 c4 27. Ke3 a3 28. Rb1 axb2 29. Rbxb2 Rxb2 30. Rxb2 Ra3 31. Rb7+ Kd6 32. Kd2 Kc5 33. f4 gxf4 34. gxf4 Rxc3 35. Kxc3 Nxe4+ 36. Kb2 Nc6 37. Rxf7 c3+ 38. Kc1 Nb4 39. Rc7+ Kd5 40. a3 Nc6 41. Bf3 1-0

