1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 (2... e5 {This is the Albin Countergambit. The best Black can achieve is to reach a much worse or lost position. This opening is only good enough for blitz!} 3. dxe5 d4 4. Nf3 (4. e3 {This is a famous trap and the reason why White plays 4.Nf3 and 5.a3.} Bb4+ 5. Bd2 dxe3 6. Bxb4 exf2+ 7. Ke2 fxg1=N+ 8. Rxg1 (8. Ke1 Qh4+ 9. g3 Qe4+ $19) 8... Bg4+ $19) 4... Nc6 5. a3 $1 {The best move. White gains control over the b4-square and wants to play e3 next.}) (2... Nc6 {The Chigorin variation. It used to be considered risky for Black, but with the advancement of the computers, the modern engines condemn it. Here is a very straightforward way to play against it!} 3. cxd5 Qxd5 4. e3 {White is threatening to play Nc3 and d5 with tempo which would lead to a big advantage.} e5 {The only chance for Black to fight back, otherwise White gets a big advantage with simple moves.} 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. a3 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 {White has an advantage in this position and plans to continue with c4 next.}) 3. Nc3 c6 (3... Bb4 {This is a playable move that White can try to take advantage of by transposing to a good version of the Nimzo-Indian with e3.} 4. e3 Nf6 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 {White's idea is to capture on d5 and play Bd3. Black can capture on c4 first, but Black will be a tempo down compared to a Nimzo-Indian where White usually spends a tempo with Bd3 first and then Bxc4.}) 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Nc3 {This is a good way to avoid the main theoretical lines after 6.Bd2 Qxd4 and go for a slight advantage!} *

