1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c6 {This is a playable line for Black. Usually, the main lines tend to be better but also more theoretical.} 4. e4 {This is my recommended move for White, although White also has some other playable options.} (4. cxd5 {This is kind of a lazy move that is playable.} exd5 5. Bf4 {It resembles the Queen's Gambit a bit where Black hasn't played the moves a6 or h6, so Black will develop the pieces immediately and has a slightly better version of that opening, however, the position is still playable for White.}) (4. Nf3 dxc4 {The position gets complicated where White sacrifices a pawn and Black tries to hold on to the pawn with b5, but the position is playable.} (4... Nf6 {Black also has this option which is very theoretical and transposes to the Semi-Slav.})) (4. e3 {Is another option that White can try. Black has a choice of continuing with the natural 4...Nf6, or even play:} f5 {Playing a Stonewall set-up.}) 4... dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ {Black needs to act quickly, otherwise, White will consolidate the position and will have a very comfortable advantage.} (5... Nd7 $6 {Black's doesn't have time to play slow moves like this one since White will consolidate the position and will have a nice advantage.} 6. Nf3 Ngf6 7. Nxf6+ Nxf6 8. Bd3 Bb4+ 9. Ke2 $14 {9.Bd2 is also good of course, but even this move which looks weird is good since the bishop on b4 is misplaced and White plans to continue with Qc2, Rd1, and then hide the king back on f1.} (9. Bd2 Bxd2+ 10. Qxd2 O-O 11. O-O-O $1 $16)) 6. Nc3 {This is a good move which is slightly worse than 6.Bd2, although it's very practical as it doesn't require learning a lot of theory.} (6. Bd2 {This is objectively the best move.} Qxd4 7. Bxb4 Qxe4+ {White has different options such as 8.Be2 or 8.Ne2. This is a playable position but highly impractical due to the high amount of theory that has been developed. White won't get it as often as the main lines but will need to spend a lot of time studying it.}) 6... c5 {The best move for Black by far.} (6... Nf6 7. Nf3 O-O 8. Bd3 {White has a comfortable advantage.} (8. a3 {Is also possible.})) 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 {White has the bishop pair and potential attacking possibilities on the Black king, while Black has some long-term advantages, namely White's weaknesses on the queenside.} Nf6 9. Nf3 O-O (9... Qa5 {This is the best try from Black.} 10. Bd2 Ne4 {Black needs to act quickly.} (10... O-O 11. Bd3 {The queen isn't doing anything on a5 now.}) 11. Bd3 Nxd2 12. Qxd2 {White still has some attacking chances, potentially with playing d4-d5 at some point, although Black can enter an endgame from this position.} cxd4 13. cxd4 Qxd2+ 14. Kxd2 {This position with the hanging pawns is a good version for White.} Nd7 (14... Nc6 15. Rab1 $14) 15. a4 {White wants to play a4-a5 and fix Black's queenside pawns, regardless if Black plays b6 or not. White can also continue with Rhb1 and Kc3 or Ke3 later.} Ke7 16. a5 $16) 10. Bd3 Nbd7 11. O-O {White has a big advantage since the pieces are being developed naturally and Black doesn't have the time to put pressure on the doubled pawns.} b6 12. Ne5 (12. Bg5 {This is also possible.}) 12... Bb7 (12... Nxe5 $2 {This move allows White a free hand on the kingside.} 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. Bf4 {It's very difficult and slow for Black to put pressure on the doubled pawns, so White will continue to develop and will create an attack against Black's king. The move 14.f4 is not as good since it would have blocked the dark-squared bishop.} (14. Qh5 {This move would have been very strong but Black has the response 14...f5.} g6 $2 (14... f5 $14) 15. Qf3 $18 {Attacking the rook on h8 and planning to defend the e5-pawn with either Re1 or Bf4 next.})) 13. Bg5 cxd4 (13... Nxe5 14. dxe5 Be4 {Black may be able to get a playable position with this move, although Black is still worse.}) 14. cxd4 Qc7 15. Re1 Nxe5 16. Rxe5 Rfd8 17. Re3 b5 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Qh5 Kf8 20. Qxh7 Rac8 21. d5 e5 22. Bf5 bxc4 23. Bxc8 Rxc8 24. Rd1 Qd6 25. Rg3 Ke7 26. Rg7 Rf8 27. Qe4 c3 28. Qc2 Qxa3 29. d6+ Ke6 30. Rg3 Qb2 31. Rxc3 Qxc2 32. Rxc2 Bc8 33. Rc7 Bd7 34. Rxa7 f5 35. f3 f4 36. Kf2 Rb8 37. h4 f5 38. Re1 Rh8 39. Ra5 Rxh4 40. Rexe5+ Kxd6 41. Rad5+ Kc6 42. Rd4 Rh7 43. Rxf4 Rf7 44. Rd4 1-0

