1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nc3 e6 4. e4 dxe4 5. Nxe4 Bb4+ 6. Nc3 c5 7. a3 Bxc3+ 8. bxc3 Nf6 9. Nf3 O-O 10. Bd3 Nbd7 11. O-O Qc7 12. Re1 b6 13. Ne5 Bb7 (13... Nxe5 {If Black wants to capture on e5, it's better to capture on d4 first.} 14. dxe5 {The pawn on e5 gives White space advantage and the ideal circumstances to start an attack against Black's king.} Nd7 15. Bf4 Bb7 {The position where White has a pawn on e5 with only one open file gives White a big advantage.} 16. Qg4 $18 {White's pieces are joining the attack and it's unlikely that the game will last very long. On the other hand, Black's pieces are passive.}) 14. Bf4 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Qc6 {This is a very good positional move for Black which helps avoid immediate defeat.} (15... Nd7 {Now both 16.Qh5 or 16.Qg4 give White a winning position.} 16. Re3 $2 {The idea is to transfer the rook to the kingside and meet Qc6 with Qg4 or Rg3 for example, but here White lost the advantage because of:} f5 $1 {Be careful of the f5-push! White can't capture en passant since the bishop on f4 will be lost.}) 16. f3 Nd7 17. Bc2 {This is a very interesting move, threatening both Ba4 and Qd3.} Rfe8 $6 (17... Rfd8 18. Bg5 $16) 18. Ba4 $18 b5 19. Bxb5 Qb6 20. Bxd7 Red8 21. Qa4 h6 22. Rab1 Qc7 23. Rxb7 Qxb7 24. Bc6 Qb2 25. Bxa8 g5 26. Qa5 Rxa8 27. Be3 Rb8 28. h4 Qc2 29. Qxc5 gxh4 30. Qd4 Rb2 31. Bf2 h3 32. gxh3 Kh8 33. c5 Qf5 34. c6 Rb8 35. c7 Rg8+ 36. Qg4 Qh7 37. Rd1 f5 38. Qxg8+ Qxg8+ 39. Kh2 Kh7 40. Rd8 Qg7 1-0

