1. d4 d5 2. c4 {The Chigorin variation. It used to be considered risky for Black, but with the advancement of the computers, the modern engines condemn it. Here is a very straightforward way to play against it!} Nc6 3. cxd5 $1 Qxd5 4. e3 $1 {Again, White's idea is to play Nc3 and d5 with tempo which would lead to a big advantage.} e5 $1 {The best move for Black.} 5. Nc3 Bb4 6. a3 $1 {This simple move appears to be the best. White is strengthening the center and is ready to mobilize the pieces with tempo.} Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 Qd6 $5 {Black's idea is to not allow c3-c4.} (7... Nf6 8. c4 Qd6 9. d5 Ne7 10. a4 $1 {White has a very good position and no need for further theory. White intends to activate the dark-squared bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal.} Nd7 (10... Qb4+ 11. Qd2 $14 (11. Bd2 $16)) (10... O-O 11. Ba3 Qd8 12. Nf3 $16 (12. Ne2 $16)) 11. Ba3 Nc5 (11... c5 12. Ne2 O-O 13. Nc3 f5 14. Be2 $16 Ng6 15. f3 $5 (15. O-O e4 16. Nb5 $16) 15... e4 (15... f4 16. Ne4 $18) 16. f4 $18) 12. Ne2 b6 13. Nc3 {Threatening Ne4.} Qg6 14. Bxc5 $1 bxc5 15. Qb1 $3 Bf5 (15... Qxb1+ 16. Rxb1 {Black's idea with the Chigorin is to get an active position, instead, Black got an inferior position out of the opening which will need to be defended for a long time. White is much better.}) 16. Qb5+ Bd7 17. Qxc5 c6 18. d6 Nf5 19. Qxe5+ Be6 20. c5 O-O 21. Bd3 Qxg2 22. Be4 Qg4 23. h3 Qh5 24. Rg1 g6 25. Bxc6 Rab8 26. Bd5 Rb2 27. Bxe6 fxe6 28. d7 Rd8 29. c6 Kf7 30. c7 Nh4 31. Qxh5 Rxd7 32. Qxh4 {1-0 Kukhmazov,A-Egorov,E/Chess.com INT 2020/CBMs}) 8. a4 {White continues with the typical plan of developing the dark-squared bishop on the a3-f8 diagonal.} Nge7 (8... exd4 9. cxd4 Qb4+ 10. Qd2 {10.Bd2 is slightly better, but this is a nice example of the endgame which can arise.} Qxd2+ 11. Bxd2 Nf6 12. f3 O-O 13. Bb5 Bd7 14. Ne2 a6 15. Bd3 {White's intention was to develop quickly, not capture on c6 except potentially in a case where it doubles the Black pawns.} Rfe8 16. Kf2 {White has a winning advantage and it's important to note that White is pushing the pawns carefully. White has developed the pieces, there are no weaknesses, and White solidified the position, so now the central pawns can soon start to advance, or there is another option first which is to expand on the kingside too.}) 9. Nf3 O-O (9... Qg6 10. Ba3 Bg4 (10... e4 11. Nd2 $16) 11. h3 $16) 10. Ba3 Qf6 11. Be2 (11. Nxe5 {This is an improvement that leads to a very pleasant position for White.} Nxe5 12. dxe5 Qxe5 13. Qd4 $16) 11... Rd8 12. O-O Bg4 13. Nd2 Bxe2 14. Qxe2 Nd5 15. Rfc1 {White has stabilized the position and now White will slowly increase the advantage.} Qg6 16. Qf3 f5 17. c4 e4 18. Qg3 Qxg3 19. hxg3 Nb6 20. a5 Nd7 21. Rcb1 b6 22. a6 Nde5 23. Rb5 g6 24. Kf1 Nd3 25. Ke2 Rd7 26. g4 Rf8 27. gxf5 gxf5 28. g4 Rxd4 29. Bxf8 1-0

