1. c4 e6 2. Nc3 d5 3. d4 Bb4 $5 {This is a playable move which is a hybrid between the Nimzo-Indian, the Queen's Indian, and the Ragozin. White can use this move by transposing to a good version of the Nimzo-Indian with e3.} 4. e3 $1 Nf6 5. a3 $1 Be7 {This will not solve Black's problems since White has gained an extra tempo.} (5... Bxc3+ {This move is far more common, taking the game into a Nimzo-Indian territory with a better version for White.} 6. bxc3 O-O (6... c5 7. cxd5 $1 exd5 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Ne2 $14) (6... c6 $5 {This is the only independent try for Black. In my opinion, White should undouble the pawns with cxd5 followed by an immediate c4! Check the games to see this idea in practice.} 7. cxd5 $1 cxd5 8. c4 $1 $14 b6 9. cxd5 $1 exd5 (9... Qxd5 10. f3 $14 (10. Ne2 $5 O-O 11. Nf4 Qd7 12. Bb2 Ba6 13. Bxa6 Nxa6 14. Qe2 $14)) 10. Bb5+ $3 {This is a typical idea that disturbs the coordination of the Black pieces and it prevents Ba6 because it distracts either the knight or the bishop to d7.} Bd7 (10... Nbd7 11. a4 $16) 11. Bd3 Nc6 12. Ne2 $1 $16) 7. cxd5 $1 exd5 8. Bd3 c5 9. Ne2 $14) 6. Nf3 O-O 7. b4 {White took advantage of the extra move a3 to push b4 immediately.} Nbd7 8. Bb2 c6 9. c5 {This move is a good idea when White has some pieces developed and when the structure can be kept intact. Carlsen probably evaluated that Black isn't on time to play e5, or Black will manage to play e5 and will be worse.} Qc7 10. Bd3 (10. Be2 e5 11. O-O e4 12. Nd2 {This position is objectively better for White because White's attack is faster on the queenside, although f3 can be also considered at some point, however, Black is not without chances too and should try to build up an attack against White's king which can be dangerous, especially in blitz.}) 10... e5 11. dxe5 Nxe5 12. Nxe5 Qxe5 13. Qc2 $14 Qh5 14. Ne2 Ng4 15. h3 Ne5 16. Bxh7+ Qxh7 17. Qxh7+ Kxh7 18. Bxe5 {White won a pawn and went on to win the game.} b6 19. Nd4 Bd7 20. Rc1 Rfc8 21. Ke2 Kg6 22. Rc3 f6 23. Bf4 b5 24. Bd6 Bd8 25. g4 a5 26. Kf3 axb4 27. axb4 Ra4 28. Rb3 Rca8 29. h4 Ra2 30. h5+ Kh7 31. Rhb1 R8a6 32. R3b2 R2a3 33. Kg3 f5 34. Nxf5 Bf6 35. Rd2 Bxf5 36. gxf5 1-0

