1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c6 (5... Nf6 6. cxd5 exd5 7. e3 {White plans to continue with Bd3 and Ne2 next.} (7. Bg5 {This move looks natural but the plan is to play with e3 and f3, when the same plan can't be executed now because of 0-0, Re8, and h6, where White will have difficulties defending the e3-pawn. It's better to leave the bishop on c1.}) 7... Bf5 8. Ne2 {Moves like a4 or c4 are typical, while Bd3 is also an idea. I would recommend gaining a tempo with Ne2-Ng3 and only then exchanging the light-squared bishops.} O-O (8... Ne4 9. f3 $16) 9. Ng3 Bg6 10. Bd3 {Sooner or later Black has to exchange the bishops, otherwise White will capture on g6.} Bxd3 11. Qxd3 Nbd7 12. O-O {White can aim to play a plan with c4, or f3-e4, in both cases with a small advantage.} c5 13. c4 dxc4 14. Qxc4 cxd4 15. Qxd4 $14) 6. e3 Nf6 7. cxd5 {This is the best move in my opinion, exchanging the doubled pawns.} cxd5 8. c4 {White wants to capture on d5 on the next move where White will have a small advantage.} b6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Bb5+ {White plays this Bb5+ typical idea in order to prevent Ba6.} Bd7 11. Bd3 O-O 12. Nf3 (12. Ne2 $16 {The knight is heading to the g3 or f5-square from where it will stand better.} Nc6 13. O-O Re8 {White can choose from different moves in this position, such as Nf4, Ng3, Bd2, many moves are good.}) 12... Bc8 13. Qe2 {Provoking a5 in order to exchange the light-squared bishops. White could have also simply castled short.} a5 14. a4 Ba6 15. Ba3 Re8 16. Bb5 Bxb5 17. Qxb5 Qd7 18. Qb3 Nc6 19. O-O Ne4 20. Rfc1 Rab8 21. Rc2 Nd8 22. Qb5 Qxb5 23. axb5 f6 24. Rac1 Ne6 25. Rc6 Kf7 26. Kf1 Rb7 27. Ke2 Rd8 28. Nd2 Nxd2 29. Kxd2 Ng5 30. f3 Ne6 31. Kd3 Rdd7 32. g3 Rbc7 33. Rxb6 Rxc1 34. Bxc1 Rc7 35. Rc6 Rxc6 36. bxc6 Ke7 37. Ba3+ Kd8 38. e4 dxe4+ 39. fxe4 Kc7 40. d5 Ng5 41. Kd4 Nf3+ 42. Kc5 Ne5 43. d6+ Kc8 44. Kd5 a4 45. Bb2 Nd3 46. Bc3 a3 47. d7+ Kc7 48. Ba5+ Kb8 49. d8=Q+ 1-0

