1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 b6 6. f3 d5 7. cxd5 exd5 8. e3 O-O 9. Bd3 Ba6 10. Ne2 {It's better to not exchange on a6.} c5 11. O-O {It's usually better when the pawn is back on f2 since it would allow White more flexibility. Here, the pawn was committed to the f3-square earlier.} Bxd3 12. Qxd3 Re8 13. Ng3 Nc6 {Black is putting pressure on the d4-pawn in order to prevent e3-e4 from White. Usually if White manages to play e4 without any tactical drawbacks, White will have a huge advantage.} 14. Bb2 Qd7 (14... c4 {This is a big positional mistake since Black is not putting pressure anymore and Black's counterplay is much slower than White's idea of pushing e4.} 15. Qd2 {The bishop on b2 will be activated through the c1-square at some point.} Na5 16. Rae1 Nb3 17. Qc2 $16 {The maneuver Na5-Nb3 didn't achieve anything and misplaced the knight.}) 15. e4 {Black should capture on e4 since allowing e4-e5 without an exchange on e4 can become very dangerous, with ideas such as Nf5-Nd6 or f4-f5 coming.} dxe4 16. fxe4 {The problem with the move Qd7 is that Black doesn't defend the knight on f6 anymore, so White can consider Rxf6 at some point.} Ne5 17. Qa6 Nc6 18. Qd3 Ne5 19. Qe2 Ng6 20. Rxf6 {This is a good positional sacrifice.} gxf6 21. Rf1 Re6 22. d5 Re5 23. c4 {White isn't in a rush to capture the rook on e5 because the bishop on b2 is even stronger than the rook.} Rae8 24. Bxe5 Rxe5 25. Rxf6 Qa4 26. Qf1 b5 27. Rc6 Qxa3 28. cxb5 Qe3+ 29. Kh1 Nf4 30. Rf6 Nd3 31. Rf3 1-0

