1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 $6 {This is the Albin Countergambit. The best Black can achieve is to reach a much worse or lost position. This opening is only good enough for blitz!} 3. dxe5 d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. a3 {The best move. White gains control over the b4-square and wants to play e3 next.} Nge7 (5... Bg4 $5 {This move is very common but remember that Black isn't really threatening to capture on f3!} 6. h3 $1 ({Another possibility is:} 6. g3 Bxf3 7. exf3 Nxe5 8. f4 Nc6 9. Bd3 $16 Qe7+ {Keeping the queens on the board is better for White because White's king will be very safe on the kingside.} (9... a5 10. O-O Nf6 11. Nd2 Be7 12. Nf3 $16 (12. Ne4 $16)) 10. Kf1 O-O-O 11. Kg2 $16) 6... Bh5 (6... Bxf3 7. exf3 Nxe5 8. f4 Nc6 9. Bd3 {It's extremely difficult for Black to put pressure on the bishop on d3, so White has a good blockade, controls a lot of squares, and has the bishop pair, White already has a big advantage.} (9. b4 $16 {Is also possible.}) 9... Qe7+ 10. Kf1 $1 $16) 7. Nbd2 Qe7 8. g4 Bg6 9. b4 Nxe5 10. Nxe5 (10. Nxd4 $4 Nd3#) 10... Qxe5 11. Nf3 $16) (5... Bf5 $2 6. e3 $1 d3 {Once Black plays d3, the pawn is too far advanced without enough support, so it will be lost.} 7. Nc3 Nge7 8. e4 Bg4 9. Qxd3 Qxd3 10. Bxd3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nxe5 12. Be2 O-O-O 13. Be3 $18) 6. b3 $5 {White's idea is to simply develop the pieces with Bb2 and Nbd2.} (6. b4 $1 {This is the best move according to the theory with an advantage for White.} Ng6 (6... Bg4 7. h3 Bxf3 8. exf3 Nxe5 9. f4 $16) 7. Bb2 a5 8. b5 Ncxe5 9. Qxd4 Qxd4 10. Bxd4 Nxc4 11. e3 Nd6 12. Nbd2 $14 (12. h4 $14)) 6... Bg4 (6... Ng6 $5 7. e3 $14) 7. h3 Bxf3 {The bishop can retreat to h5 but then the bishop will be out of play, so it needs to stay on the c8-h3 diagonal.} 8. exf3 $16 Nxe5 9. f4 N5c6 10. Bd3 {This position is already strategically winning for White. The reason is that Black doesn't have access to the d3-square and there is no way to put pressure on the light-squared bishop.} g6 11. O-O Bg7 12. Nd2 O-O 13. b4 a5 14. b5 Nb8 {Intending Nb8-Nc5, but White calculated that there is enough time to prevent Black's plan.} 15. a4 c5 {Now there is a pawn on the c5-square, so the bishop on d3 remains inaccessible.} (15... Nd7 16. Ba3 {Preventing Nc5. If Black plays c5, the c5-square won't be available for the knight anymore and the bishop from a3 can later be activated through the c1-square.}) 16. Qf3 Ra7 17. Re1 Nd7 18. Ne4 b6 19. Bd2 (19. Ra2 {This is an interesting idea for White, transferring the rook to the e-file via the 2nd rank.} Nf5 20. Rae2 {Black's pieces are hitting in the d4-pawn, so they are passive.}) 19... Qa8 20. Ng5 Qxf3 21. Nxf3 Nc8 22. f5 $1 {White used the opportunity to undouble the pawns.} Nd6 23. fxg6 fxg6 24. Re6 Rf6 25. Rae1 Nf8 26. R6e2 Nf7 27. Re8 Nd6 28. Rb8 Rb7 29. Rxb7 Nxb7 30. Be4 Nd6 31. Bd5+ Kh8 32. Ne5 h6 33. g4 g5 34. Kg2 $1 Kh7 35. Kg3 $1 Ne8 36. f4 gxf4+ 37. Bxf4 Nc7 38. Be4+ Kg8 39. Nc6 Nce6 40. Bd5 Rxf4 41. Rxe6 Nxe6 42. Bxe6+ Rf7 43. Nd8 d3 44. Bxf7+ Kf8 45. Bg6 1-0

