1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 d5 {Objectively, White's best moves are 4.Nc3 where Black has a lot of options, or 4.g3 which leads to a lot of theory.} 4. cxd5 exd5 {The reason why this is a slightly worse version for White compared to the same position with a knight on c3 instead of f3, is that White is putting some pressure on Black's center and can prevent Black's Bf5 move.} 5. Qc2 $5 {The reason why White plays 5.Qc2 is to prevent Bf5 for now and to provoke the move g6. Black has several plans and move orders to choose from, while White wants to continue with Bg5 or Bf4 next. There's no need to memorize any concrete theory and there are some sample lines below demonstrating the typical plans and ideas of this line for both sides.} (5. Nc3 $5 {This is a very natural move that is also playable.}) (5. Bg5 $5 {Is another option that White can play.}) 5... c6 (5... Bb4+ $6 6. Bd2 {6.Nc3 is also possible, but 6. Bd2 seems to be the best move.} Bxd2+ 7. Nbxd2 {Usually the knight is developed on c3, however, the knight is also well placed on d2 in this position.} O-O 8. e3 c6 9. Bd3 $14 {White wants to avoid the exchange of Black's light-squared bishop and then continue with a minority attack on the queenside.} Bg4 10. Ng5 $1 (10. Ne5 {This move is also good for White.}) 10... h6 11. Nh7 $14) (5... c5 $6 6. dxc5 Qa5+ (6... Na6 7. Bg5 Nxc5 8. e3 h6 9. Bxf6 Qxf6 10. Nc3 $16 Be6 11. Bb5+ $18) 7. Bd2 Qxc5 {White has an advantage both in the endgame after 8.Qxc5 and after the move 8.Bc3.} 8. Qxc5 (8. Bc3 $14 Ne4 9. e3 Nc6 10. a3 Nxc3 (10... Bf5 11. Bd3 $14) 11. Nxc3 $14) 8... Bxc5 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Rc1 Be7 11. e3 $14) (5... g6 {Black wants to develop the bishop on f5.} 6. Bg5 $1 (6. Bf4 $1 {6.Bg5 is good, although this move is also possible.} c6 7. e3 {White wants to continue with Bd3 which would prevent Bf5 from Black, where the g6 move would become pointless, so Black should play Bf5 in this moment.} Bf5 8. Bd3 Bxd3 9. Qxd3 Nbd7 10. Nbd2 Be7 {The position may be equal with perfect play, however, there is a long battle ahead where both sides have chances.} 11. h3 O-O 12. O-O Re8 {The position may be slightly favorable for White, when the plans are conducting the minority attack, or playing f3-e4 at some point.} 13. Rfc1 $14) 6... c6 (6... Bf5 7. Qb3 {Puts pressure on Black's position.}) 7. Nc3 Bf5 $2 {Black always needs to be careful when playing Bf5.} (7... Bg7 {Black needs to protect the f6-knight in order to play Bf5. The bishop is slightly misplaced on g7 but not as much as in the Exchange Slav since in this position, the queenside is still not open as much.} 8. e3 Bf5 (8... O-O $2 9. Bd3 $16 {White successfully prevented the move Bf5.}) 9. Bd3 (9. Qb3 $5 {Is another interesting idea that White can play.} Qb6 10. h3 $5 (10. Nd2 $5 {Intending to recapture with the knight on b3 is also possible.} Nbd7 11. h3 O-O 12. Be2 Qxb3 13. Nxb3 a5 14. a4 {With an interesting battle ahead.}) 10... Qxb3 11. axb3 $14 Nbd7 12. b4 Ne4 13. Bf4 $14 (13. Nxe4 Bxe4 14. Nd2 $14)) 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O 11. O-O Nbd7 12. b4 $14 {White wants to continue with b4-b5.} b5 {Black is preventing b4-b5 and intends to play Nb6-Nc4.} 13. a4 a6 14. a5 {Preventing Nb6. The plan is to maneuver the c3-knight to the b3-square, in order to be ready to jump to c5.} Qe7 {Black also wants to use the c4-square with Ne8-Nd6, however, Black needs to spend some time to unpin the knight on f6.} 15. Na2 Qe6 16. Rac1 Ne4 17. Bf4 Rac8 18. h3 $14 {Whenever Black plays Nd6, White can simply exchange it with Bxd6. White's plan is to continue with Rc2 and then first Nc1-Nb3, and only then bring the other rook to the c-file.}) 8. Qb3 $16 {There is no proper way to defend the pawn on b7 since Qb6 is not possible due to the hanging knight on f6.} b6 9. e4 $3 $18) (5... Nc6 $5 6. a3 g6 (6... Bd6 7. Nc3 a6 8. Bg5 $14) 7. Bg5 Bg7 {The bishop is now misplaced on the g7-square.} 8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O 11. Nbd2 $14 (11. Nc3 $14)) 6. Nc3 g6 $5 (6... Be7 7. h3 (7. Bg5 $5 O-O 8. e3 Nbd7 9. Bd3 Re8 10. h3 $14 Ne4 (10... Nf8 11. O-O g6 12. Ne5 N6d7 (12... Ne6 13. f4 $1 (13. Bh6 {Is also good.} Bf8 14. Bxf8 Rxf8 15. f4 Ng7 16. g4 $16 Nd7 17. Nf3 Re8 18. Rae1 $16) 13... Ng7 14. g4 $16) 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. f4 f6 15. Ng4 $16) 11. Bf4 $14 {This is the typical move after Black jumps Ne4, with a good position for White.}) 7... O-O 8. Bf4 Re8 (8... g6 9. e3 Bf5 10. Qb3 Qb6 11. Nd2 Nbd7 12. g4 Be6 13. Bd3 Qxb3 14. Nxb3 a5 15. a4 Nb6 16. Nc5 $14) (8... Be6 9. e3 Nbd7 10. Ng5 $14) 9. e3 Nbd7 10. Bd3 Nf8 11. O-O Bd6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 13. Rab1 (13. Ne5 $14) 13... Ng6 14. b4 $16) (6... h6 $5 {If it was White to move again, White would have played the move Bg5, so 6...h6 makes some sense, preventing Bg5.} 7. Bf4 Bd6 8. Bxd6 Qxd6 9. e3 Be6 {It's good to keep in mind that White doesn't want to exchange Black's light-squared bishop.} (9... O-O 10. Bd3 Re8 11. h3 Nbd7 12. O-O b6 13. Rac1 Bb7 14. Nh4 Nf8 15. Nf5 Qd8 16. Ne2 Ne6 17. b4 (17. f3 $14) 17... a5 18. a3 $14) 10. Bd3 Nbd7 11. h3 a5 12. O-O O-O {White can continue with a3-b4, Na4 and then Nc5 supported by a rook on c1, or even Ne2-Nf4 is an idea.} 13. Rfe1 Qe7 14. a3 Ne8 15. Ne2 Nd6 16. Nf4 $14) (6... Bd6 7. Bg5 Nbd7 (7... h6 $2 {Blunders a pawn.} 8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Nxd5 Qd8 10. Nc3 O-O 11. e3 $18 Re8 (11... Bg4 12. Be2 Nd7 13. O-O Nf6 14. Ne5 Bxe2 15. Qxe2 Bxe5 16. dxe5 Nd7 17. f4 Qe7 18. Rad1 Rad8 19. Ne4 f6 20. Qc4+ Kh8 21. exf6 Nxf6 22. Rxd8 Rxd8 23. Nxf6 Qxe3+ 24. Kh1 gxf6 25. h3 Qe7 26. Qc2 Rg8 27. Qf5 Rg3 28. Kh2 Qg7 29. Rf2 Re3 30. g4 Qe7 31. Qg6 Qg7 32. Qc2 Qe7 33. Rd2 Re1 34. Kg3 Qe3+ 35. Kh4 Rh1 36. Rd8+ Kg7 37. Rd7+ Kf8 38. Qg2 Qe1+ 39. Kh5 Qf1 40. Qxf1 Rxf1 41. Rxb7 Rxf4 42. Kxh6 Rf2 43. Kg6 Rh2 44. Kxf6 {[%emt 0:00:23] 1-0 Arkell, K-Ribeiro,M/Chess.com INT 2021/Mega2021 Update}) 12. Be2 Nd7 13. O-O Nf6 14. h3 Bc7 15. Rfd1 Be6 16. e4 Qc8 17. Bf1 Nh5 18. d5 cxd5 19. exd5 Bf5 20. Bd3 Bxh3 21. gxh3 Qxh3 22. Bh7+ Kh8 23. Qf5 Nf4 24. Ne1 Rxe1+ {0-1 Arkell, K-Havanecz,B/chess.com INT 2021}) 8. e3 O-O 9. Bd3 h6 10. Bh4 Re8 11. O-O {With a standard position for this variation. Castling long can run into ...b5 ideas, and it's more often played when the knight is on e2 instead of the f3-square.} Nf8 {White has a choice from several plans in this position, from which Rab1 with b4 is the minority attack, striking in the center with e4 is also possible, and even Ne5 with f4 is an idea sometimes when the e5-square is available for a knight jump.} 12. Rae1 Bg4 13. Nd2 Bh5 {The move Rae1 doesn't just support the e4-push, but it has another role in the position.} (13... Qc7 14. Bxf6 $16) 14. f4 $16 {White wants to continue with h3-h4 while the e3-pawn is defended by the rook, and the weak e4-square is very well controlled by many White pieces.} Ng6 15. Bxg6 Bxg6 16. f5 Bh7 17. e4 $16) (6... Na6 $6 7. a3 g6 8. Bg5 Bg7 9. e3 Bf5 10. Qd1 (10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 $14) 10... Nc7 11. h3 $14) 7. Bg5 Bg7 $6 {The bishop is misplaced on the g7-square.} (7... Be7 $1 {This is probably the best line for Black in this system.} 8. e3 (8. Bxf6 $5 {Capturing on f6 may be also playable. It leads to an equal position with chances for both sides.} Bxf6 9. e3 Bf5 10. Bd3 Bxd3 11. Qxd3 O-O 12. O-O Nd7 13. b4 $11) 8... Bf5 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 {And now follows a very sophisticated bishop dance, in order to finally exchange the bishop under the best circumstances.} 11. Bh6 $5 (11. O-O O-O 12. Rab1 a5 13. Bxf6 (13. a3 Re8 14. Rfc1 Ne4 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. Nd2 Nd6 17. h3 Kg7 18. Na4 Rec8 19. Nc5 Nf6 20. b4 a4 21. Qc2 Nb5 22. Ra1 Ra7 23. Nxa4 Qc7 24. Nc3 Nxa3 25. Rxa3 Rxa3 26. Nb5 cxb5 27. Qxc7 Rxc7 28. Rxc7 Ra1+ 29. Kh2 Ra2 30. Nf3 Rxf2 31. Rxb7 Ne4 32. Rxb5 Nc3 33. Rb7 Nd1 34. Kg1 Rb2 35. Ne5 Nxe3 36. g4 Nc2 37. b5 Nxd4 38. b6 Kf6 39. Nxf7 Nf3+ 40. Kf1 d4 41. Nd6 Nd2+ 42. Ke1 d3 43. Rb8 Nf3+ 44. Kf1 Nh2+ 45. Kg1 Nf3+ 46. Kf1 Nh2+ 47. Kg1 d2 48. Ne4+ Kg7 49. Nxd2 Rxd2 50. b7 Rb2 51. Rc8 Nf3+ 52. Kf1 Rxb7 53. Kf2 Ng5 54. h4 Ne4+ 55. Kf3 Nf6 56. g5 Rb3+ 57. Kf4 Rb4+ 58. Ke5 Re4+ 59. Kd6 Nh5 60. Rc7+ Kg8 61. Rc8+ Kf7 62. Rc7+ Kf8 63. Rc8+ Re8 64. Rc7 Ng7 65. Kd5 Re7 66. Rc8+ Ne8 {0-1 Rustemov,A-Svane,R/chess.com INT 2022}) (13. Qc2 Re8 14. a3 Ne4 (14... Nb6 15. Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Nd2 Nc8 17. b4 axb4 18. axb4 b5 19. Ne2 Qb6 20. Rfc1 Ra6 21. Ra1 Rxa1 22. Rxa1 Be7 23. Qc3 Bd6 24. Nb3 Ne7 25. Nc5 Qc7 26. g3 Qc8 27. Ra7 Qg4 28. Kf1 Nf5 29. Nd7 Nxe3+ 30. fxe3 Qf3+ 31. Ke1 Rxe3 32. Nf6+ Kg7 33. Ne8+ Kh8 {0-1 Abdulla,A-Ghosh,D/Dhaka BAN 2022}) 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 16. b4 Nd6 17. b5 Nc4 18. bxc6 bxc6 19. Rb7 Reb8 20. Rxb8+ Rxb8 21. Qa4 Qd6 22. Ra1 Rb2 23. e4 Ndb6 24. Qd1 Nxa3 25. exd5 cxd5 26. h3 Nac4 27. Qc1 Rb3 28. Ne2 a4 29. Qh6 Qf8 30. Qh4 a3 31. Nf4 h6 32. Ne5 Nxe5 33. dxe5 g5 34. Qg4 Rb4 35. g3 Kh8 36. Qf5 gxf4 37. e6 Re4 38. exf7 Kg7 39. Rxa3 Qxa3 {0-1 Hovhannisyan,M-Sterck,A/Belgium 2020/CBMs}) 13... Nxf6 14. Qc2 Bd6 15. a3 Qe7 16. Rfe1 Rfe8 17. h3 Kg7 18. Re2 Ne4 19. Nxe4 Qxe4 20. Qxe4 Rxe4 21. b4 Re7 22. Reb2 h6 23. bxa5 Rxa5 24. Rxb7 Rxb7 25. Rxb7 Rxa3 26. g3 Kf6 27. Kg2 Ra2 28. Rb6 Rc2 29. g4 Ke7 30. Rb7+ Ke6 31. Ra7 Rb2 32. h4 Rb4 33. Ra6 Kd7 34. Ne1 Rb3 35. Ra8 Bb8 36. Nd3 Rxd3 37. Rxb8 Ke7 38. Rh8 Kf6 39. Rxh6 Kg7 40. g5 c5 41. dxc5 d4 42. exd4 Rxd4 43. Kg3 Rc4 44. h5 Rxc5 45. f4 Rc3+ 46. Kg4 Rc1 47. hxg6 fxg6 {0-1 Megaranto,S-Delchev,A/Chess.com INT 2020/CBMs}) (11. Ne5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Bf4 O-O 14. O-O Re8 15. Bg3 Bc5 16. f4 f6 17. Nxd5 cxd5 18. Qxd5+ Kg7 19. Rad1 Bxe3+ 20. Kh1 Nc5 21. Qf3 Bd4 22. Bh4 g5 23. fxg5 fxe5 24. Qf7+ Kh8 25. g6 Qxh4 26. g7# {1-0 Reimanis,R-Sveshnikov,V/Lichess.org INT 2020/ Mega2020 Updates}) 11... Bf8 12. Bf4 Nh5 (12... Be7 13. h3 O-O 14. g4 {This move may be too ambitious since Black is solid enough to face this attack.} (14. O-O $1 Re8 15. Rfc1 $132) 14... Re8 15. O-O-O Qa5 16. Kb1 Bb4 17. Nd2 Bxc3 18. Qxc3 Qxc3 19. bxc3 Ne4 20. Nxe4 Rxe4 21. h4 f6 22. Kc2 b5 23. g5 fxg5 24. hxg5 Nb6 25. Be5 Nd7 26. Bd6 Re6 27. Bf4 a5 28. Rb1 a4 29. Rh4 Rf8 30. Kd3 Nb6 31. Rbh1 Rf7 32. Be5 Nc4 33. Bf6 h5 34. Rf4 Rf8 35. Re1 Rfe8 36. Rh4 Kf7 37. Rh3 Re4 38. Re2 Rg4 {[%emt 0:00:27] 1/2-1/2 Nigalidze,G-Lortkipanidze,N/Tbilisi 2021/Mega2021 Update}) 13. Bg5 (13. O-O-O Nxf4 14. exf4 Bd6 15. g3 Qf6 16. Rde1+ Kd8 17. h4 h5 18. Ne5 Nb6 19. Qc2 Re8 20. Re3 Re7 21. Rhe1 Rc8 22. Kb1 Rcc7 23. a4 a5 24. Qb3 Nc8 25. Ka1 Qf5 26. Nd1 Bb4 27. R1e2 Qf6 28. Nc3 Nd6 29. Rd3 Nf5 30. Nd1 Qg7 31. Rc2 f6 32. Nf3 Qf8 33. Nc3 Qe8 34. Na2 Re2 35. Nxb4 axb4 36. Ka2 Rxc2 37. Qxc2 Qe4 38. Qb3 Re7 39. Rd1 Qe2 40. Rd2 Qe4 41. Rd1 b5 42. a5 Ra7 43. Qd3 Rxa5+ 44. Kb3 Qxd3+ 45. Rxd3 Ra1 46. Kxb4 Rf1 47. Rd2 Nd6 48. Re2 Ne4 49. Nd2 Rxf2 50. Rxf2 Nxf2 51. Nf1 Ne4 52. Kb3 Kd7 53. Kc2 Ke6 54. Kd3 b4 55. Kc2 c5 56. dxc5 Nxc5 57. Ne3 Ne4 58. Kb3 d4 59. Nc2 Nxg3 60. Nxd4+ Kd5 61. Nc2 Nf5 62. Nxb4+ Ke4 63. Kc4 Kxf4 64. Nd5+ Ke5 65. b4 g5 66. Nb6 gxh4 67. Nd7+ Kf4 68. Nxf6 h3 {0-1 Lupulescu,C-Schitco,I/Chennai IND 2022}) 13... Be7 14. Bh6 Bf8 15. Bxf8 Kxf8 16. O-O Kg7 17. b4 Re8 18. b5 Nhf6 19. bxc6 bxc6 20. Rfc1 Qa5 21. Ne2 Rac8 22. Nd2 Qb5 23. Nf4 Ne4 24. Nxe4 dxe4 25. Qa3 Nf6 26. Qxa7 Ra8 27. Qc5 g5 28. Ne2 h6 29. Ng3 Qxc5 30. Rxc5 Reb8 31. h3 Ra6 32. Nf5+ Kh7 33. Rac1 Rb5 34. Ne7 Rxa2 35. Rxc6 Nd5 36. Nf5 f6 37. R6c5 Rxc5 38. Rxc5 Nb4 39. Rc7+ Kh8 40. Ng3 Ra1+ 41. Kh2 f5 42. Nxf5 Rf1 43. Kg3 Nd3 44. Kg4 Rxf2 45. Nxh6 Rxg2+ 46. Kh5 Nf4+ 47. exf4 gxf4 48. Ng4 Kg8 49. Nf6+ Kf8 50. Nxe4 f3 51. Rc5 Re2 52. Rf5+ Kg7 53. Ng3 Re3 54. Kg4 Rd3 55. Rf4 f2 56. Nf5+ Kg6 57. Rxf2 Rd1 58. Nh4+ Kh6 59. Nf3 Kg6 60. Rd2 Ra1 61. d5 Kf6 62. d6 Ra4+ 63. Rd4 Ra8 64. d7 Rd8 65. Kf4 Ke6 66. Ne5 Rh8 67. Nf7 Rh4+ 68. Kg5 Rxd4 69. d8=Q {1-0 Gledura, B-Prohaszka,P/Ajka HUN 2022}) (7... Bf5 $2 8. Qb3 $16 Bc8 9. e4 dxe4 10. Ne5 Qe7 11. Bc4 $18) 8. e3 Bf5 9. Bd3 (9. Qb3 $5 Qb6 10. h3 Nbd7 11. Nd2 O-O 12. Be2 $11) 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 O-O 11. O-O Nbd7 12. b4 (12. h3 Qb6 13. Rab1 a5 14. Qc2 Rfe8 15. Rfc1 Qa6 16. Bf4 Ne4 17. Nxe4 Rxe4 18. Nd2 Ree8 19. Nb3 Bf8 20. Nd2 a4 21. Nf3 Bg7 22. Ne1 Nb6 23. b3 a3 24. Nd3 Nd7 25. Nc5 Nxc5 26. Qxc5 Bf8 27. Qc3 Qb5 28. Rd1 Bb4 29. Qd3 Qxd3 30. Rxd3 Re6 31. Rc1 Rae8 32. Bc7 f5 33. h4 h6 34. g3 g5 35. hxg5 hxg5 36. Kg2 Kf7 37. Rdd1 R6e7 38. Be5 Kg6 39. Rh1 Rh7 40. Rxh7 Kxh7 41. g4 Kg6 42. Kg3 {1-0 Gomez Ledo,R-Abuin Boullon,M/Santiago de Compostela ESP 2022}) (12. Rab1 a5 13. Rfc1 Qe7 14. h3 Rfe8 15. Qc2 h6 16. Bh4 Qe6 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. a3 Bf8 19. b4 axb4 20. axb4 b5 21. Ne2 Rec8 22. Nf4 Nb6 23. Nd3 Nc4 24. Ra1 Qf5 25. Qc3 Bd6 26. Nfe1 h5 27. Rxa8 Rxa8 28. Ra1 Ra4 29. Rxa4 bxa4 30. Nc2 g5 31. Na3 Nxa3 32. Qxa3 g4 33. hxg4 hxg4 34. g3 Qe4 35. Kf1 Bxg3 36. fxg3 Qxe3 37. Qc3 Qf3+ 38. Ke1 Qxg3+ 39. Kd2 Qg2+ 40. Ke3 Qf3+ 41. Kd2 g3 42. Qxc6 g2 43. Qe8+ Kh7 44. Qe1 a3 45. Qh4+ Kg7 46. Qg5+ Kh7 47. Qh4+ Kg7 48. Qg5+ Kf8 49. Qd8+ Kg7 50. Qg5+ {1/2-1/2 Akobian,V-Vokhidov,S/chess.com INT 2022}) 12... b5 13. a4 a6 14. a5 {Prevents the d7-knight from reaching the c4-outpost through the b6-square.} Qe7 15. Rab1 Qe6 16. Rfc1 (16. Bf4 $14 Nh5 17. Ne2 $16) 16... Ne8 {The knight is heading to the d6-square and then to c4.} 17. Ne2 Rc8 18. Bf4 {Black is ready to play Nd6, but at the moment Black plays it, White will exchange the knight.} Nd6 19. Bxd6 $16 1-0

