1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 d5 3. c4 e6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Qc2 c6 6. Nc3 Be7 7. h3 $5 {The idea is that if Black plays g6, White can develop the bishop to h6 without stopping on the f4-square, therefore gaining the move h3 which is useful.} O-O (7... g6 8. Bh6 $1 Bf5 9. Qb3 $5 (9. Qc1 $5 {Is also possible.} Nbd7 10. g4 Be4 11. Bg2 $14) 9... Qb6 10. e3 {Intending g4.} Qxb3 (10... Nbd7 11. g4 Be4 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Bd3 Qxb3 (13... Bb4+ 14. Ke2 $14) 14. axb3 a6 15. Ke2 $14 {The pawns on b3 and b2 are doubled but Black can't put any pressure on them. White can even use them at some point by bringing a knight to d3 and then playing b4. White is enjoying a risk-free advantage.}) 11. axb3 Nbd7 12. Nd2 a6 13. g4 Be6 14. f3 $14 (14. Bd3 $14) 14... Bf8 15. Bxf8 Kxf8 16. b4 $16) 8. Bf4 g6 {Giri waited for the move Bf4 and only now plays g6.} (8... Re8 $6 {These types of positions are playable for Black but are a bit passive.} 9. e3 Nbd7 (9... Be6 10. Bd3 Nbd7 11. O-O $14) 10. Bd3 Nf8 11. O-O Ng6 12. Bh2 Bd6 13. Bxd6 Qxd6 14. Rab1 $14) (8... Bd6 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 10. e3 Re8 11. Bd3 $14) 9. e3 (9. g4 $5 {It's a matter of taste whether White wants to play riskier or not.} Na6 10. e3 Nc7 (10... Nb4 11. Qc1 a5 12. a3 Na6 13. Bd3 $13) 11. Bd3 Ne6 12. Bh6 $14) 9... Bf5 10. Qb3 Qb6 11. Nd2 Nbd7 12. g4 Be6 13. Bd3 Qxb3 14. Nxb3 a5 15. Nd2 a4 16. a3 b5 17. f3 Nb6 18. Ke2 Ra7 19. Bc2 Rfa8 20. Rhc1 b4 21. axb4 Bxb4 22. Bd3 Nc4 23. Bxc4 dxc4 24. e4 a3 25. bxa3 Rxa3 26. Rxa3 Rxa3 27. Ndb1 Rb3 28. Bh6 Ne8 29. Rc2 f5 30. Bd2 fxe4 31. fxe4 h5 32. Ra2 hxg4 33. hxg4 Bxg4+ 34. Ke3 Bf8 35. Kf4 Be6 36. Kg5 Kf7 37. Kh4 Nd6 38. Ra7+ Rb7 39. Ra6 Nb5 40. d5 cxd5 41. exd5 Bf5 42. Nxb5 Be7+ 43. Bg5 Bxg5+ 44. Kxg5 Rxb5 45. Ra7+ Ke8 46. Nc3 Rb3 47. Ne2 Rb2 48. Nf4 c3 49. Rc7 c2 50. Nxg6 Kd8 51. d6 Bxg6 52. Kxg6 Rb6 53. Rxc2 Rxd6+ 54. Kf5 1/2-1/2

